commit_message:
Make backup and snapshot use objects

This makes the backup and snapshot paths use objects.  To make things
cleaner for syncing compute rpcapi and cells rpcapi, the
single snapshot_instance rpc method that was used for both snapshot and
backup has been split into backup_instance and snapshot_instance.  The
appropriate cells versions have been added.

The backup and snapshot tests have also been converted into unit tests and
moved into test_compute_api.py.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: Ibdaee07290cf8d61c106702aa7068dd308bc9aac

commit_message:
Make inject_network_info use objects

Makes the inject_network_info path use instance object.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I8d6b90cac0c1f638b623def319f676e95b416e09

subject: Convert reset_network to use instance object

commit_message:
Convert reset_network to use instance object

Converts all calls to reset_network to use objects.  Also adds the
cells rpcapi methods to match compute rpcapi and ditches the special
cells code in compute/cells_api.py

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: If4da142864cbe993a7cc852358e3b27bd8c02629

commit_message:
Make compute_api use objects for lock/unlock

Converts compute_api.lock and unlock to require objects and modifies the
callers to pass them.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: Ice8361328cdfeb92207c778beb07b55a9d4eda8d

commit_message:
Proof of concept of kexec/takeovernode

Exploration of the possibility of reusing a node by pulling down a
known image and blowing away the contents of the current running
machine.

Change-Id: I2de449b867c802a9235984935fd9bad0490ecf6c

[{'created': '2013-08-14 22:14:27.000000000', 'message': 'Use pbr AUTHORS generation

pbr has a feature to generate AUTHORS files at sdist time from the git
commit logs. swift, however, has a header section that the project likes
at the top of the file. Recent pbr supports keeping that information in
an AUTHORS.in file and will pre-pend it to the generated output.

Move the AUTHORS file to AUTHORS.in, remove the info that can come from
the git log, and enable the flag for the feature in pbr.

Change-Id: Icd882c3426b4f166b2e75a7f1d425e4c13962e52
'}]
commit_message:
Use pbr AUTHORS generation

pbr has a feature to generate AUTHORS files at sdist time from the git
commit logs. swift, however, has a header section that the project likes
at the top of the file. Recent pbr supports keeping that information in
an AUTHORS.in file and will pre-pend it to the generated output.

Move the AUTHORS file to AUTHORS.in, remove the info that can come from
the git log, and enable the flag for the feature in pbr.

Change-Id: Icd882c3426b4f166b2e75a7f1d425e4c13962e52

commit_message:
Add affinity availability zone scheduler filter.

Create an new filter to schedule the instance on a same/different availability
zone of a set of instances. And add some tests for the filter.

DocImpact

Implemented bp: different-availability-zone-filter

Change-Id: I948d8cf6ad5bab8db82398fb3aa7797a49acdc5e

commit_message:
IBM storwize_svc driver change for FC zone mgr testing

This is a WIP patch to help with the testing of FC zone
manager. The initialize_connection and terminate_connection
code has been changed to return initiator_target_map.

See review https://review.openstack.org/#/c/41772/ and
BP: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/cinder/+spec/cinder-fc-zone-manager
for details.

Change-Id: I23306e751471753b25d218acb48bd5c3b8bc86a0

commit_message:
Add support for pip to source-repositories

Adds a pip type to the source-repositories interface. elements
installing from pip can use this to allow the process running di-b
override source location.

Still a WIP, TODO :
    a bit more testing
    implement caching (when DIB_OFFLINE is set)

Change-Id: I4a8c844f58cea979e96671b7216718be3bfc66cb

Fixes bug 1202484
If we delete an instance after a confirming resize operation,
and if the instance is deleted firstly at the dest compute node,
then the *_resize dir and network info of this instance will be
left alone on the source compute node, never be cleaned up.
Please refer the bug page to get the reproduce steps.

commit_message:
Fixes race cond between delete and confirm resize

If we delete an instance after a confirming resize operation,
and if the instance is deleted firstly at the dest compute node,
then the *_resize dir and network info of this instance will be
left alone on the source compute node, never be cleaned up.
Please refer the bug page to get the reproduce steps.

Fixes bug 1202484

Change-Id: I1daa432c17ff8bd62e05f8e23503459953bb45d3

subject: Fix a race condition in add_tunnel_endpoint()

Gary, you are definitely right on that's an edge case and it's fairly hard to reproduce this bug in production environment. Anyway, I believe, we should take into account even such extreme cases.

I would like to use @lockutils.synchronized, but that would not work if we had more than one running Quantum service."}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Restored'}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Gary, thank you for taking your time to look over this change!  I'd definitely like to receive a portion of reasonable criticism from core devs on if it's a good way to fix the problem.

In order to reproduce the bug easily I actually had to cheat a bit: I modified the OVS agent to call tunnel_sync() multiple times on start and used 2-3 agent instances running concurrently. Duplicate entries appeared almost immediately then.

I wish it was possible to fix this without making changes to DB schema, but as far as I understand relying on lockutils.synchronized() is not enough (because we can have a few Quantum API instances running at the same time). 

try/except inside for loop looks hacky too, but again, as far as I understand, simply running two queries within a single transaction would depend on the transactions isolation value set in your RDBMS."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Fix a race condition in add_tunnel_endpoint()

If there are multiple OVS agents concurrently executing
'tunnel_sync' RPC call a race condition can occur
leading to insertion of two different TunnelEndpoint
entries having the same 'id' value.

Unfortunately, we can not rely on:
  - @lockutils.synchronized(), because a Neutron installation can use
    more than one API node
  - with_lockmode('update'), because it works differently in PostgreSQL
    comparing to MySQL and doesn't guarantee that no new rows have been
    added to the table since the select query was issued. Please take a
    look at http://www.postgresql.org/files/developer/concurrency.pdf for
    more details.

The proposed fix:
  - ensures there is a unique constraint set for 'id' column
  - wraps creation of a new TunnelEndpoint entry into a
    repeatedly executed transactional block (so even if a concurrent
    DB transaction has been flushed or commited earlier than this one
    we can handle an integrity error and try again, in spite of the
    specified transactions isolation level value)

Fixes bug 1167916

Change-Id: I62dc729d595f090436199d5e1b6b98a884ead7a5

Fix is_package_installed() check with dpkg

is_package_installed() incorrectly returned '0' for packages that
had 'un' status in the dpkg database.

commit_message:
Add recent neutron extentions and IB support

Additions to Mellanox Plugin:
Add ML2 compatibility support.
Enable Infiniband Network Type.
Keep the compatibility to Linux Bridge Plugin to allow Network node deployment via Linux Bridge L2 Agent.
Add support for Host Port Binding and L3/DHCP Agent Scheduler.

Implements: blueprint mlnx-plugin-improvments

Change-Id: Ieca518bbd07a39258cd14ceeecd3f9d3e2b6f219

This should give a significant boost in delete performance for large objects. By "performance" I mean that the latency for a delete of a large file will be the same as the latency for a small file. This shifts the delete overhead into either the local object-replicator or object-server handling a REPLICATE operation. By "large", I mean anything over 10M.

I had thought of proposing a similar change, but I would have done something like this in case anyone is uncomfortable with leaving .ts files around until the reclaim_age expires:

    self.lazy_delete = config_true_value(conf.get('lazy_delete', 'true'))
    ...
    if not self.lazy_delete:
        disk_file.unlinkold(metadata['X-Timestamp'])'}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2013-08-13 10:13:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

It's still unlinking old files synchronously with the request in this change.

I wouldn't want stale data files regularly laying around for a full replication pass, but launching whatever unlinkold-equivalent in a fire-and-forget background thread or similar should be fine.  Maybe I'll do that after this goes in or doesn't go in."}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2013-08-13 11:52:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
get rid of unlinkold

We currently have two methods for cleaning up object directories - unlinkold in
the object server and hash_suffix in the replicator.

This modifies the object server to reuse the more complete hash_suffix logic.

Change-Id: Id2fd83caad979bfd446d52a775a1fa373a670cf1
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Use correct filename for index & serial file when setting permissions

There was a cut-n-paste bug where self._set_permissions() was called
with the exact same filename, self.ssl_config_file_name, instead of
the index and serial filenames. This patch uses the index and serial
filenames as was the original intent.

Change-Id: I571c766ac746bbbc1bedfdf1ff2b1b86363a0af0
Fixes: bug #1206254

commit_message:
Pass objects for revert and confirm resizes

The revert_resize and confirm_resize compute API methods were previously
converted to accept and use objects.  This actually passes them over RPC
instead of their primitive forms.

Implements blueprint unified-object-model

Change-Id: I6dbd5fc0ddcaa37013e885b71aabede92eedf120

commit_message:
Implement interruption-free update and rollback

During an update, where a resource must be replaced in its entirety, create
the replacement resource before deleting the old resource.

Also, allow rollback to the previous version of the resource without
replacing it, where that is possible.

Fixes bug #1176142

Change-Id: Id89654bad297815bdbcc86f666367772889b5df4

commit_message:
Fix the help messages to specify image/flavor name

User can specify flavor/image name as the arguments of "nova boot"
command instead of their ids, but the help messages does not explain
that. This fixes the help messages.

Fixes: bug #1211156

Change-Id: I47813c8ebbe5fc83d627f016e3751918b3ab11cb

commit_message:
Drop support for diablo to essex migrations

This removes support for the following legacy-related commands:

    $ keystone-manage export_legacy_catalog
    $ keystone-manage import_legacy
    $ keystone-manage import_nova_auth

DocImpact

Change-Id: If7277e912f11c9bf3bec15f9addd848e0774f14f

commit_message:
Deprecate classes with hyphens

Puppet does not recommend the use of hyphens in class names.

This change deprecates classes with hyphens and inform the users
to use the new ones. Backward compatibility is preserved.

Change-Id: I4991c956e297d76423a805558d9b6731473a4a51
(cherry picked from commit 0f7601a3587511b633d0a04ffa24f42f19b3786c)

commit_message:
Remove unused var DEFAULT_MAX_CACHE_SIZE

In file: glance/image_cache/__init__.py, DEFAULT_MAX_CACHE_SIZE
is never used after declared, remove it and make glance code
tidy and pleasing.

Change-Id: I208f1dc63e2bc95bb6be94fdc88f9bfce069f67c

commit_message:
Use implicit nullable=True in sqlalchemy model

In sqlalchemy nullable defaults to True, so we don't need to explicitly
set the value to the default.  By removing all nullable=True everywhere
it makes it easier to spot the nullable=False and also should lead to
less confusion when adding a new column (do I need to add nullable or
not, only some other columns do it)

Change-Id: I22fe2d0caca77005553a6a6f0c7cc2d3e8ea5512

commit_message:
Adds Flavor ID validations

* Flavor ID should not contain special symbols.
* Flavor ID should be in range 1-255 characters.
* Flavor ID should not have leading/trailing whitespaces.

Fixes LP Bug 1202136
DOCIMPACT

Change-Id: I63c36811a57982e826f22f827f86d40ff6a6210e

And adding 3 wrapper methods create_notification, update_notification, and delete_notification. 

This would make implementing notifications in keystone a bit easier. Currently the generic send_update(old res, new res, resource) model is: 1) hard to read and 2) easy to mess up (i.e: mis-placed None variable).

[{'created': '2013-08-21 04:29:58.000000000', 'message': 'Refactored meter statistics map functions

Refactored the meter statistics map functions MAP_STATS and MAP_STATS_PERIOD
to remove duplicate code

Change-Id: I6954abe9d8c86c780ad96bbf04849d068b360b1c
'}, {'created': '2013-08-22 03:04:13.000000000', 'message': "Implements partial group by stats for MongoDB

Implements: blueprint api-group-by

Adds group by meter statistics in the MongoDB driver for the case where the
groupby fields are a combination of 'user-id', 'resource-id', 'project-id', and
'source' (metadata fields not implemented) and where period = None

Refactors the meter statistics map functions MAP_STATS and MAP_STATS_PERIOD to
remove duplicate code

Change-Id: I6954abe9d8c86c780ad96bbf04849d068b360b1c
"}, {'created': '2013-08-22 05:15:20.000000000', 'message': "Adds group by statistics for MongoDB driver

Implements: blueprint api-group-by

Adds group by meter statistics in the MongoDB driver for the case
where the groupby fields are a combination of 'user-id',
'resource-id', 'project-id', and 'source' (metadata fields not
implemented)

The group by meter statistics works with query filtering and period
parameters

Refactors the meter statistics map functions MAP_STATS and
MAP_STATS_PERIOD to remove duplicate code

Modifies test_group_by_unknown_field in class StatisticsGroupByTest
so that it works for both the SQL Alchemy driver and the MongoDB
driver; the previous version only worked for the SQL Alchemy driver

Change-Id: I6954abe9d8c86c780ad96bbf04849d068b360b1c
"}, {'created': '2013-08-22 16:57:17.000000000', 'message': "Adds group by statistics for MongoDB driver

Implements: blueprint api-group-by

Adds group by meter statistics in the MongoDB driver for the case
where the groupby fields are a combination of 'user-id',
'resource-id', 'project-id', and 'source' (metadata fields not
implemented)

The group by meter statistics can be requested with query filtering
and/or period parameters.  In this case, the query filtering and/or
period grouping is applied first, followed by the calculation of
group by meter statistics.

Refactors the meter statistics map functions MAP_STATS and

commit_message:
Adds group by statistics for MongoDB driver

Implements: blueprint api-group-by

Adds group by meter statistics in the MongoDB driver for the case
where the groupby fields are a combination of 'user-id',
'resource-id', 'project-id', and 'source' (metadata fields not
implemented)

The group by meter statistics can be requested with query filtering
and/or period parameters.  In this case, the query filtering and/or
period grouping is applied first, followed by the calculation of
group by meter statistics.

Refactors the meter statistics map functions MAP_STATS and
MAP_STATS_PERIOD to remove duplicate code

Modifies test_group_by_unknown_field in class StatisticsGroupByTest
so that it works for both the SQL Alchemy driver and the MongoDB
driver; the previous version only worked for the SQL Alchemy driver

Change-Id: I6954abe9d8c86c780ad96bbf04849d068b360b1c

commit_message:
xenapi: devstack support for raw tgz image upload

Devstack will recognise the .xen-raw.tgz extensions, and upload them to
glance as raw tgz images with xen pv_mode. This change also adds "tgz" to
the recognised container formats of glance. The changes for raw tgz
support are:

    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40908/
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40909/
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/41651/

related to blueprint xenapi-supported-image-import-export

Change-Id: I077564587d4303291bb4f10d62bb16380b574106

In original Swift, the format of hashes.pkl is:

[{suffix1: md5(timestamps)}]

With a comparasion of local_hash and remote_hash, we could
figure out which suffix directory is missing object

While for EC Reconstructor, we need to know the exact missing
chunk so we could do the later fix work. The new format is:

{suffix1: {hash: md5(timestamp1)},...}

Thus with a comparison of local_hash and remote_hash, we could
figure out the missing object.

bp: ec-reconstructor

Change-Id: I281ddbb6249f8134696f2f308d20616f85a2af12
'}]
commit_message:
Adding per object hash into hashes.pkl

In original Swift, the format of hashes.pkl is:

[{suffix1: md5(timestamps)}]

With a comparasion of local_hash and remote_hash, we could
figure out which suffix directory is missing object

While for EC Reconstructor, we need to know the exact missing
chunk so we could do the later fix work. The new format is:

{suffix1: {hash: md5(timestamp1)},...}

Thus with a comparison of local_hash and remote_hash, we could
figure out the missing object.

bp: ec-reconstructor

Change-Id: I281ddbb6249f8134696f2f308d20616f85a2af12

commit_message:
Add update method of security group name and description

make it possible to edit the name and description of
common security groups, we can not rename the default.

Fixes: bug #918393

[{'created': '2013-08-27 11:18:57.000000000', 'message': 'Fix the message of coverage directory error

If a coverage-report directory conflicts, the error message is
incomplete like the following:

$ nova coverage-start --combine
Coverage collection started
$
$ nova coverage-report --html test01
Report path: /tmp/nova-coverage_Krl__k/test01
$
$ nova coverage-start --combine
Coverage collection started
$ nova coverage-report --html test01
ERROR: Directory conflict: %s already exists (HTTP 400)
$

This patch fixes the message.

Fixes bug #1217315

Change-Id: Ie21b0e87262a3caef36d93711ee96529ec699cec
'}]
commit_message:
Fix the message of coverage directory error

If a coverage-report directory conflicts, the error message is
incomplete like the following:

$ nova coverage-start --combine
Coverage collection started
$
$ nova coverage-report --html test01
Report path: /tmp/nova-coverage_Krl__k/test01
$
$ nova coverage-start --combine
Coverage collection started
$ nova coverage-report --html test01
ERROR: Directory conflict: %s already exists (HTTP 400)
$

This patch fixes the message.

Fixes bug #1217315

commit_message:
Switch run_tests.sh to run in parallel by default

This commit switches run_test.sh to run in parallel by default. Since
the tox jobs were moved to parallel by default run_tests.sh should
have the same behavior.

[{'created': '2013-08-19 02:04:37.000000000', 'message': "Implement native nova server resource

Some notes on the implementation:
- extends Resource rather than Instance since most of the
  complexity of Instance is in the handling of the Volumes
  attribute
- exposed properties and attributes map as closely as possible
  to the underlying v1 nova API (rather than the nova client library)
- property or attribute key namespaces have been stripped to provide
  a cleaner API and avoid YAML quoting.
  (eg instance_name -> 'OS-EXT-SRV-ATTR:instance_name')
- an assumption is currently made that any volumes specified
  in block_device_mapping should not be detached on suspend
- Network address properties attempt to cater for simple and
  advanced use-cases:
  - 'first_private_address' and 'first_public_address' for simple
    template attribute scenarios, and to aid with AWS::EC2::Instance
    transition
  - 'networks' for a simple data structure which provides all addresses
  - 'addresses' for the raw data structure returned by the API

Implements blueprint native-nova-instance
Change-Id: I4136da22961c8aa90e3fc8a9411457622f1909fb

commit_message:
Implement native nova server resource

Some notes on the implementation:
- extends Resource rather than Instance since most of the
  complexity of Instance is in the handling of the Volumes
  attribute
- exposed properties and attributes map as closely as possible
  to the underlying v1 nova API (rather than the nova client library)
- property or attribute key namespaces have been stripped to provide
  a cleaner API and avoid YAML quoting.
  (eg instance_name -> 'OS-EXT-SRV-ATTR:instance_name')
- an assumption is currently made that any volumes specified
  in block_device_mapping should not be detached on suspend
- Network address properties attempt to cater for simple and
  advanced use-cases:
  - 'first_private_address' and 'first_public_address' for simple
    template attribute scenarios, and to aid with AWS::EC2::Instance
    transition
  - 'networks' for a simple data structure which provides all addresses
  - 'addresses' for the raw data structure returned by the API

Implements blueprint native-nova-instance
Change-Id: I4136da22961c8aa90e3fc8a9411457622f1909fb

There is only one file "heat.pot" in heat/locale/.
We need to add the missing heat.po files.
I updated "heat.pot" file and added the supported languages
(Take glance po files as reference).
The added files are used for
setting up the structure of directory.
The po file doesn't have any translated strings.

Fixes bug #1217172

Change-Id: I1e017c332c80eb01b04e042b5da0129198169bd5
'}]
commit_message:
Add the missing heat.po files into heat

There is only one file "heat.pot" in heat/locale/.
We need to add the missing heat.po files.
I updated "heat.pot" file and added the supported languages
(Take glance po files as reference).
The added files are used for
setting up the structure of directory.
The po file doesn't have any translated strings.

Fixes bug #1217172

Change-Id: I1e017c332c80eb01b04e042b5da0129198169bd5

commit_message:
Move create_volume flow to a subfolder

In order to start splitting up the create_volume flow into
smaller files we will start by moving the create_volume.py
file to a folder with just __init__.py and this will then
act as the base for create_volume task modules.

Also add in a utils file that contains to start the commonly
used debug listener attachment mechanism.

Change-Id: Ie2fd0c77bb04f8153afecdce75588614b48fed8a

commit_message:
show details when nova-manage command fails

I submit a patch for nova-mange db archive_deleted_rows It passed
unittest but failed in tempest , I extract the related code from
tempest ,and run it in my local system and It didn't get error,
We really need know what happend when failing.

Change-Id: I43e1c800a2e8f7afaf19893fa82f252e3ec6bdc0

so previously we haven't been installing -dev packages as devstack. I think if we're going to do that, we probably need to move those to another package file so that it's clear what's dev vs. run. Interested in dtroyer's pov here."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2013-07-26 11:20:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Sean, makes sense. But I would be happy to have a running development system after calling stack.sh. At the moment I always have to install those 6 noted packages to be able to use run-tests.sh of the several projects on a fresh environment.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-07-26 16:07:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Yuo know, we're all about development here, right? ;)  I don't necessarily mind the -dev packages, but am now wondering a) why only glance? and b) how long has this been an issue?  It feels like a bit of a corner case that I'd like to understand better."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2013-07-30 00:25:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

it definitely exists for other packages as well. Maybe if we had a # dev comment in line we could take in the -devel packages and just know the difference.

People use devstack for living documentation on what's working, so I think we should be explicit on runtime vs. development deps."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2013-07-30 05:05:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Dean: Only Glance, because I tested some of my changes for Glance on a fresh Devstack environment and stumbled upon those  missing packages. There are also missing packages for Nova (nearly the same as for Glance) and I think also for the other components.

Introducing a tag for development packages sounds like a good idea. Is # devel sufficient? I would then update this review request.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-07-30 15:07:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Good ideas there.  A tag in the prereq files would be the functional parallel to requirements.txt vs test-requirements.txt.

Proposal:  Agg a 'devonly' tag (unlikely to have a false positive from an actual comment) to the prereq files and add INSTALL_DEVONLY_PACKAGES=yes to localrc.

I think I'd prefer to see an optional second arg to get_packages() to trigger it to install devonly packages, I don't see any other global references besides $DISTRO in there now.

One alternative would be to use 'dev' as a psuedo-service and put all dev packages into a single files/{apts|rpms|suse-rpms}/dev file, then just $(get_packages dev) to collect the names..."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2013-08-14 14:57:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2013-08-14 15:15:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

recheck no bug'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-08-14 16:04:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

The more I think about this the more I come to the following:
* We need a term that isn't going to randomly pop up in a comment like 'testonly' or 'devonly'.  I'm leaning toward 'testonly' now since these are being added to support testing.
* I think the 'testonly' term needs to be logically AND-ed with the dist:DISTRO terms if both are present.  The point of 'dist:' is to handle package availability and name changes between releases and that happens with -devel packages as much as any other.  (Right now it is short-circuit boolean with dist: always evaluated first."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-14 16:35:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Adds new tag for testonly packages in package lists

Also introduces a new parameter INSTALL_TESTONLY_PACKAGES
in the stackrc with False as default value. Setting it to
True stack.sh will install all packages tagged with the tag
testonly in the package lists.

Includes needed packages for Ubuntu and Fedora

fixes bug #1203680

Change-Id: I911a6601819a34262853bba0658f6751148bfbec

commit_message:
python3: Fix imports for py2/py3

Python3 reorganized the standard library and moved several functions
to different modules. Six provides a consistent interface
to them through the fake six.moves module.

However, the urlparse, urllib2, etc modules have been combined
into one module which Six does not support so we do it via
py3kcompat.

Modules such as StringIO and CStringIO have been removed
completely so we use the io module.

Change-Id: I53adac11b634de2c710fc39def36bcec96366710
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

Added test case in test_migrations for migration 208

This patch is to add test case in test_migrations.py for migration 208.
Migration 208 was brought by commit 74b024f75403c168b5c69ee67a16d1053965e5db
(Change-Id: I72371260159c9fdffcdb57209095fc103b6dd79e)

Change-Id: I153abf260716c8af61d7ccf554d91ba80f559e60
Signed-off-by: Shane Wang <shane.wang@intel.com>

commit_message:
Fix error messages in v3 aggregate API

Since moving error messages to HTTP responses from LOG.info()s,
the error messages has been unexpected formats like:
  "Cannot delete aggregate: %s <id>"
This patch fixes them.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Iadc41ab254c1f17efdb08f23449a0bd7a94a8f6c

commit_message:
Fix aggregate creation/update with null or too long name

Fixes aggregate creation so an attempt to create an aggregate with
a null name results in a 400 Bad Request rather than 409 Conflict.
This was fixed for the V2 api in 43f9028f84ffec9b465bec10025ba75266c1bc22
and is fixed in this changeset for the V3 api

For both the V2 and V3 APIs adds a check to ensure that the aggregate
name is not longer than 255 characters.

Also fixes null or too long names when updating an aggregate

Fixes bug 1212240

Change-Id: I644a8a46f0b75e3717ecafec1889ce6316ca18c6

'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-08-22 03:47:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hmm, I'd really rather we fix setup-neutron then; the 192.0.2.1 stuff should be independent of the actual neutron API setup etc etc. We may have situations where that is the only IP available...

I'm willing to be convinced though!"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-08-26 23:51:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I've revisited this and there is no race AFAICT:
 - init-neutron-ovs doesn't call neutron, it's purely heat/json driven
 - it sets up 192.0.2.1
 - post-configure should be restarting all the agents

setup-neutron just sets up neutron policy networks, no change to http request path for APIs."}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-08-28 23:53:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Hmmm, I tried this again and it now seems to work ok, I must have screwed something up. Abandoning this change.'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-20 13:05:26.000000000', 'message': "Use $SEED_IP for seed endpoints

Looks like 192.0.2.1 can't be used until after we call setup-neutron
which can't be used until after setup-endpoints is run.

Change-Id: Ib5fff4b45ef658a53209f1253266784296e4b352
"}]
commit_message:
Use $SEED_IP for seed endpoints

Looks like 192.0.2.1 can't be used until after we call setup-neutron
which can't be used until after setup-endpoints is run.

Change-Id: Ib5fff4b45ef658a53209f1253266784296e4b352

commit_message:
Convert _poll_unconfirmed_resizes to use Migration object

We can now call the compute api directly for confirm_resize, so the
conductor method 'compute_confirm_resize' has been deprecated.

This was also the last call to conductor's:
'migration_get_unconfirmed_by_dest_compute'

so it, too, has been deprecated.

Related to blueprint unified-object-model

Change-Id: I57a4898f14d35e97d3a9ed8fd2a99f157c4111a7

cast() then just ignores the exception.

commit_message:
Raise timeout in fake RPC if no consumers found

If you do a call() with e.g. the kombu driver, and there is no consumer
listening, then you will get a Timeout exception.

However, with the fake driver, we just silently return None in this
case. The oslo.messaging fake driver instead raises a Timeout and this
behaviour change turned up a tonne of issues with Nova's unit tests.

Make this change here too so that we can merge fixes for Nova's tests
before porting to oslo.messaging.

Note that although we also raise a Timeout in the case of cast(), but
cast() then just ignores the exception.

This commit just syncs this change from oslo-incubator.

blueprint: oslo-messaging
Change-Id: I20065bcc61dda99a68143afbcf6bb96884b6eb91

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-27 23:11:18.000000000', 'message': 'Stub out instance_update() in build instance tests

Change Ife6e5aef4fda46f74e2db7be1a09b210be397152 introduced an
instance_claim() which invokes an instance_update() RPC on conductor.
However, during tests no conductor is running and this RPC would have
happily returned None. If we if we time out call()s in the fake RPC
driver when there are no consumers for a topic, then these tests will
fail.

To avoid this, simply mock out the instance_update() conductor calls.

blueprint: oslo-messaging
Change-Id: Iea010d92eadaf15b3a9e339589170a26234b3142
'}]
commit_message:
Stub out instance_update() in build instance tests

Change Ife6e5aef4fda46f74e2db7be1a09b210be397152 introduced an
instance_claim() which invokes an instance_update() RPC on conductor.
However, during tests no conductor is running and this RPC would have
happily returned None. If we if we time out call()s in the fake RPC
driver when there are no consumers for a topic, then these tests will
fail.

To avoid this, simply mock out the instance_update() conductor calls.

blueprint: oslo-messaging
Change-Id: Iea010d92eadaf15b3a9e339589170a26234b3142

commit_message:
Mock out action event calls in build instance test

action_event_start() and action_event_finish() get called during the
build instance tests and if we time out call()s in the fake RPC driver
when there are no consumers for a topic, then these tests will fail.

blueprint: oslo-messaging
Change-Id: Ib109fa9552dc6032b390c300723bb6cb72d62062

commit_message:
Make compute_api confirm/revert resize use objects

This makes the compute_api confirm and revert_resize calls use
and return Migration objects for its work.  This also adds the
cells RPC methods needed to support child cells re-calling the
compute API with objects.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I26adc8d2fadc4a31cd0de94887e163040691ede1

commit_message:
Cleanup remote console access

openstack-config/ch_consoleconfigure.xml is unused, the sections
referenced in it are included already in another place in the manual.

Also, use compute-spice-console.xml instead of the duplicated content
in common/section_compute-configure-console.xml.

Rename compute-spice-console.xml to follow the vnc example.

Change-Id: Ib5e23151a7905f11886bd9eeaf675aa0cf278372

I am not sure I fully understand this change.

I see that we use the cells_api instead of the computetask_api, and which messages down to the cells manager, that then messages down to cells own computetask worker.

Why could we not just leave the computetask_api with a single "migrate_server" method, and let that split into live/non-live down at the cell?

I know there are two separate compute_api calls, but I don't see how that affects things in this case. I guess I am miss-understanding some of the cells redirect magic?'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-08-22 09:24:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: (1 inline comment)

My bad, I think I see the issue now, we need to run the compute_api twice, so we do computetask_api->cell->compute_api->...

Could we add a migrate_server to the compute_api (same signature as the compute_task_api, or similar anyway), with a split based on live=true/false, then make resize and live_migrate private methods.

That should then mean we have a unified path between api->compute_api->cell->compute_api->compute_task_api,

Sure the code just has big ifs in compute_api and compute_task_api, but we get closer to our goal of unifying the code paths.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-08-22 09:58:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-08-22 11:24:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

Here is what I was thinking for the compute_api, that should make it possible to keep a single migrate_server call down to cells and in the compute_task api:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/43272/'}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2013-08-22 18:33:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15: (1 inline comment)

John: Yeah, I mean, I could have sent a single call down to cells still.  And I could have put the 'if live is True, call live_migrate, else call resize' logic down there.

But I felt it was a bit nicer to actually create the 2 different messages.  In a combined call, there's 1/2 of arguments that apply to cold migrate, and 1/2 of arguments that apply to live migrate.

I'd actually like to split the conductor rpcapi into 2 calls, also, but that was a little further than I wanted to go in this patch."}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2013-08-23 03:12:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

commit_message:
Make compute_api migrate/resize paths use instance objects

This converts the migrate/resize/live_migrate paths to use instance
objects.  This also syncs up cells rpcapi and compute task rpcapi so
we can ditch the special cells code in compute/cells_api.py.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I977a5edb8a5313b2a8827796ff8c2bc081f9d63f

commit_message:
Store CONF.baremetal.instance_type_extra_specs in DB

The baremetal driver supports sending back arbitrary key value pairs via
RPC for scheduling purposes.  Since the rpc fanout is being removed
store these values in the database in the ComputeNodeStat table.

A separate patch will update the compute_capabilities_filter to use
these values.

part of bp no-compute-fanout-to-scheduler

Change-Id: I03d20484cd78f9cd64dcc3d270b2882c6ab12195

[{'created': '2013-08-25 04:26:29.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor Token Provider to be aware of expired tokens.

The Token Provider was not aware of expired tokens, and would
not raise Unauthorized if a token was expired when asked
to "validate" (validate_token, validate_v2_token, validate_v3_token)
or "check" (check_v2_token, check_v3_token) it. The assumption was
that the Token driver would never return an expired token  from
the token_api.get_token method.  When token caching is implemented,
this assumption can no longer be made.

This patchset updates the provider to make it capable of inspecting
token data returned by the token validation methods on the driver.
If a token is expired it will properly raise Unauthorized.  The
provider will also raise Unauthorized if the token is in the
revocation_list.

Refactored the Token Provider to noi longer use a separate code-path
to "validate" or "check" tokens.  Check now benefits from the code
to ensure a token is still valid.

Since caching is implemented at the manager level, the expiration
check is done in the manager (above the driver), it is expected
that the manager needs to be expiration aware (responses from the
driver may be cached).

partial-blueprint: caching-layer-for-driver-calls
Change-Id: I2caa4cb47ba1d3a33746fc00f672a5b8fe319bd6

commit_message:
Refactor Token Provider to be aware of expired tokens.

The Token Provider was not aware of expired tokens, and would
not raise Unauthorized if a token was expired when asked
to "validate" (validate_token, validate_v2_token, validate_v3_token)
or "check" (check_v2_token, check_v3_token) it. The assumption was
that the Token driver would never return an expired token  from
the token_api.get_token method.  When token caching is implemented,
this assumption can no longer be made.

This patchset updates the provider to make it capable of inspecting
token data returned by the token validation methods on the driver.
If a token is expired it will properly raise Unauthorized.

Refactored the Token Provider to noi longer use a separate code-path
to "validate" or "check" tokens.  Check now benefits from the code
to ensure a token is still valid.

Since caching is implemented at the manager level, the expiration
check is done in the manager (above the driver), it is expected
that the manager needs to be expiration aware (responses from the
driver may be cached).

partial-blueprint: caching-layer-for-driver-calls
Change-Id: I2caa4cb47ba1d3a33746fc00f672a5b8fe319bd6

[{'created': '2013-08-24 02:10:29.000000000', 'message': 'Implement Caching for Token Revocation List

Based upon the Keystone caching (using dogpile.cache) implementation
token revocation list caching is implemented in this patchset.

The following methods are cached:
    * token_api.list_revoked_tokens

Calls to token_api.delete_token and token_api.delete_tokens will
properly invalidate the cache for the revocation list.

DocImpact

commit_message:
Implement Caching for Token Revocation List

Based upon the Keystone caching (using dogpile.cache) implementation
token revocation list caching is implemented in this patchset.

The following methods are cached:
    * token_api.list_revoked_tokens

Calls to token_api.delete_token and token_api.delete_tokens will
properly invalidate the cache for the revocation list.

Reworked some of the caching tests to allow for more in-depth
tests of the cache layer.

DocImpact

partial-blueprint: caching-layer-for-driver-calls
Change-Id: I2bc821fa68035884dfb885b17c051f3023e7a9f6

[{'created': '2013-08-27 17:53:26.000000000', 'message': "Fix errors when deleting route that doesn't exist

When nova network calls ip route to remove a route there can
occasionally be a race with another process in deleting the route.
This will result in an error from ip route because the route it was
trying to remove doesn't exist. However, since the expected result
was to remove the route there isn't a reason to error out. This
commit catches when the ip route command fails and logs a warning
message about the missing route.

Fixes bug 1217163

Change-Id: Ib750381636d1341062928d0abc8d3518e327935e

run occur at roughly the same time then there is a race between the

instances to go into an error state. This commit adds a global lock

commit_message:
Fix race when running initialize_gateway_device()

If multiple calls that result in initialize_gateway_device() being
run occur at roughly the same time then there is a race between the
ip route commands being run at the same time. This will cause
instances to go into an error state. This commit adds a global lock
to the initialize_gateway_device() method to prevent it from being
run at the same time to avoid this issue.

The race condition is not directly testable in unit tests because it
requires a multithreaded environment to run
initialize_gateway_device() at the same time. It was uncovered
with tempest in parallel.

Fixes bug 1217163

Change-Id: Ib750381636d1341062928d0abc8d3518e327935e

commit_message:
Don't use float() when normalize_timestamp() does it.

And add a comment to note for the curious when the current timestamp
will bump to 11 digits of seconds (which implies that one would no
longer be able to use string compare on timestamps of differing
length).

Change-Id: I823e7659c41a54915d7c9c64c9161a29e79cd48c
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Create discovery option for stress tests

Adds a decorator @stresstest which automatically sets the type
attr to "stress". It uses the testtools discover functionality to
automatically discover stress tests out of all tempest test.

It is possible to filter stress test with a given attribute type.
For instance to filter out only smoke tests that have a stress test
attribute.

blueprint: stress-tests
Change-Id: I8acf0b608cb500c2679a36a4a00ca4fa14668fad

commit_message:
Remove '--' from rand_name calls

Having two dashes in the service name was breaking the table parser
in the cli tests. Moving to parallel tempest means that the entries
created for the keystone tests may show up in the cli tests results.
This commit just switches the -- to a single dash which won't have
an issue with the cli parser.

Fixes bug 1217159

Change-Id: Id436c142fea7f681b2d6913adc87e2b80faf4681

commit_message:
Fix error where consumer is not deleted from sql

Looks like when the token sql backend was going through tokens
to delete, it didn't like if the token ref didn't have a token
field. I placed a guard in there now.

fixes bug: #1215493

recheck no bug'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-08-28 19:06:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Do not merge

To be perfectly honest, I tried to make sense of it all by reading the bug report, but I had a really hard time figuring out what the actual fix was and whether it went in to oslo or not.
That said, I feel that merging unvetted changes to help triage a issue into another openstack project is not the right way to go about this, especially this late in the release cycle. -2 for now, until we have more information.'}, {'account_id': 161, 'date': '2013-08-28 19:45:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Armondo,

That's fair. To summarize... if you're using rabbitmq, if the master node fails and a slave is promoted to the master, the slaves issue a consumer reset. This effectively cancels all consumer connections to the channel... unfortunately, the "physical" connection (socket) remains connected.

The end result of this is that when a master promotion occurs, openstack services don't reconnect and continue trying to consume from a queue whose channel has been canceled. Effectively, this causes it to lose its ability to consume, and never realize it and reconnect.

The current implementation of the impl_kombu.py only accounts for connection.connection_error exceptions, likely because the version of kombu which ships with Ubuntu 12.04 (1.4.3-1) had not yet implemented catching and populating the connection.channel_errors object.

This patch adds support to additionally catch and except on connection.channel_errors, which will make the OpenStack service retry on a channel error in the same it currently retries on a connection error.

The patch is moot if you're not running a version of kombu which supports populating the connection.channel_error object, as the code remains to catch and except on connection.connection_errors causing it to function identically to the way it used to. But, for anyone running a version of kombu > 2.1.5, it will catch and reconnect on channel_errors as well, making the overall code more robust and resilient to failure.

I call it a triage, because it addresses the low hanging fruit issue, but ultimately the entire impl_kombu.py should probably be re-written to take advantage of the (now) built-in kombu functionality we currently duplicate (such as ensuring connections are established, implementing active heartbeats, checking the entire stack for errors and reconnecting accordingly, rabbit server selection, etc.).

Either way, I understand if you don't want to merge it in this late in the game, but let's not let it fall off the radar as it is a problem which absolutely must be addressed in scenarios where people are running RabbitMQ in HA/Mirrored Queues. Without it, a master node failure and subsequent slave promotion causes all OpenStack services to stop consuming from their queues and effectively causes a complete outage of any piece of the orchestration fabric relying on consumption of message queues.'}, {'account_id': 161, 'date': '2013-08-28 19:48:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Sorry, I mean, Armando. Apologies for misspelling your name.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-08-28 20:00:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Kevin,

Thanks for the prompt explanation. It looks like Neutron already depends to a version of Kombu that supports the connection error handling:

https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/requirements.txt#L14

That said, I have nothing against this patch per se; it's just that we should pull in changes from oslo, once they merge in the project they belong. So far I see no indication that this has happened. I understand that this is kind of a chicken and egg problem. I am not 100% sure how to go about this and the lack of actual feedback from the CI is definitely not helping!"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-28 20:05:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Build failed.  For information on how to proceed, see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGithub#Test_Failures

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-28 14:21:06.000000000', 'message': 'Add the channel_errors object to connection checking

The channel errors object was added to kombu 2.1.4.
From http://kombu.readthedocs.org/en/latest/changelog.html:

All transport channel_errors lists now includes StdChannelError.

Prior to this release, the object exists, but was not populated.
By adding this object and excepting on it in the ensure method,
we are able to check both the connection and the channel to ensure
they are still established and properly consuming.

This is especially useful when using rabbitmq in HA mode as it
will close channels without closing connections when a slave is
promoted to master. The end result of which is consumers are no
longer able to retrieve messages until they re-establish their channel

Helps triage oslo bug #856764
(https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo/+bug/856764/)

Will also need to be applied to nova, cinder and any other
services which use this common rpc code

Change-Id: I92485138b545763842c3bafca2d4eb0ac1d59a78
'}]
commit_message:
Add the channel_errors object to connection checking

The channel errors object was added to kombu 2.1.4.
From http://kombu.readthedocs.org/en/latest/changelog.html:

All transport channel_errors lists now includes StdChannelError.

Prior to this release, the object exists, but was not populated.
By adding this object and excepting on it in the ensure method,
we are able to check both the connection and the channel to ensure
they are still established and properly consuming.

This is especially useful when using rabbitmq in HA mode as it
will close channels without closing connections when a slave is
promoted to master. The end result of which is consumers are no
longer able to retrieve messages until they re-establish their channel

Helps triage oslo bug #856764
(https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo/+bug/856764/)

Will also need to be applied to nova, cinder and any other
services which use this common rpc code

Change-Id: I92485138b545763842c3bafca2d4eb0ac1d59a78

While I feel that @prepareprotection decorator with the explicit call to check_enforcement feels a bit complex, the other alternatives are likely to be bigger headaches.  I far prefer this setup to direct stack inspection (I'm always leery of encouraging it due to the pitfalls that can come with it).

The only thing that might make sense in this type of context is if the traditional @protected decorator were able to take a check callback that extracted the relevant information (from *args, **kwargs) for the enforcement check .  This approach might just make it harder to follow what is going on.

At least with the @prepareprotection and explicit call to check enforcement, it is fairly clear what is being done, and where enforcement is happening."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2013-08-26 05:42:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Everything looks to be in line, and it all makes sense.

However, the more that I look at this the more that I think simply extending the original @protected to accept a callback helper method would actually make writing the code a bit easier (and easier to follow).  In the limited cases that you needed to use @prepareprotection, a helper method/function that could be run in @protected would have met the same need(s).

If you think that it would be too hard/complex (or otherwise not worth it) at this point to switch the mechanism up, it all looks good.'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2013-08-26 06:07:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Appreciate the comments.  In terms of expanding @protected to have a callback to execute more complex checking, I guess there are a couple of issues:

1) Where is the call back specified and for which methods within a particular set of entity methods (i.e. For 'Group' only a few of the methods would need the callback).  Are you thinking that the init() would set up some kind of callback dict with the method name being the key?

2) (minor) This would have to assume that it was OK to call the complex protection function at the start of the method that was needed to be protected.  This is probably OK (or at least you could write the callback functions to that it was OK)."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2013-08-26 07:07:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

I would probably make the callback function something that you pass to the decorator on a case-by-case.  If it is needed, you pass in a kwarg specifying the callback function, if it's not needed you get the standard @protected decorator.  If the callback_fn (see example below) is passed in, it is called with the same information "prep_info" variable would have had in it.  I wouldn't try and make init setup a dictionary, it would likely be even harder to maintain.   The real downside to this type of decorator is that if the method that is decorated changes arguments, it is possible you might have to adjust the decorator callback method (a little harder to maintain).

Example:
  @protected(helper_callback=awesome_helper_callback)
  def method(args, kwargs):
      ...

I think the biggest advantage is that there isn't a need to call an explicit check_protection, and it also means the methods on the controller(s) do not need to have their signatures changed if they are decorated.

The second issue you bring up is definitely a bit more work, but just requires making sure it's safe to call the callback at the start of the method; probably some extra lifting to validate input is sane.  This is why I wasn't sure if it was too much added complexity/not worth it, which case I don't see any issues with how this is implemented now.'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2013-08-27 14:53:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 17.'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2013-08-27 14:56:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

passed into the call. However, there are many cases where you want
to also check attributes of the entities an API is operating upon.  The
classic example is ensuring a domain administrator cannot delete users,
groups or projects outside of their domain.

This patch is just an example of an implementation on a few APIs to
obtain feedback on the approach.

'}, {'created': '2013-08-07 08:16:50.000000000', 'message': 'Implement API protection on target entities

API policy protection is currently limited to using the parameters
passed into the call. However, there are many cases where you want
to also check attributes of the entities an API is operating upon.  The
classic example is ensuring a domain administrator cannot get, update or
delete users, groups or projects outside of their domain.

This patch enables lines in the policy file to also refer to any field
in the target object of the API call. It is implemented in such a way
that it provides scaffolding that would allow us to easily implement

commit_message:
Implement API protection on target entities

API policy protection is currently limited to using the parameters
passed into the call. However, there are many cases where you want
to also check attributes of the entities an API is operating upon.  The
classic example is ensuring a domain administrator cannot get, update or
delete users, groups or projects outside of their domain.

This patch enables lines in the policy file to also refer to any field
in the target object of the API call. In addition, it includes a separate
sample policy file that shows how to use domains and the new protection
ability to provide domain segregation and administration delegation.
This sample file is also tested to ensure that such protection works
correctly.

DocImpact

Implements bp policy-on-api-target

Change-Id: Ie1a4e14a86d27e8b60e6c17e33dd6b9fa889660c

commit_message:
Create a new base REST API interface

* restapi module provides basic REST API support
  * uses dicts rather than Resource classes
  * JSON serialization/deserialization
  * log requests in 'curl' format
  * basic API boilerplate for create/delete/list/set/show verbs
* ignore H302 due to urllib import

Change-Id: I3cb91e44e631ee19e9f5dea19b6bac5d599d19ce

commit_message:
Use default value for protocol and action

Closes-Bug: #1217212

In fwaas, the server side supports default value of protocol and
action in firewall_rules resource, the CLI should support too.

Change-Id: I7a9db200528303868d8a9ab05f35a70d99bfb118

commit_message:
Fix regression that causes Timeouts to return 500

When the hacking changes were put in, one of the exceptions that were
fixed didn't also add a catch for Timeout, which causes certain timeouts
to cause a 500 return

Change-Id: I7a9db200528303868d8a9ab05f35a70d99bfb118

@Daniel, in honest, we want to use the qga to collect the monitor info of the guest, and we may not use the libvirt APIs to get the data as I commented in patch set 7, and we will interact with qga directly through the socket file on the host.
but I think qga will be useful for grace shutdown, VM heartbeat and aslo cloud monitor project like ceilometer, I will try to add grace shutdown operation and os-status of instance(which means the OS of VM is active or not, currently the ACTIVE just meanning the VM is booting on the host, the os is not 'ACTIVE') to nova."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2013-08-02 12:22:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

> @Daniel, in honest, we want to use the qga to collect the monitor info of the guest, and we may not use the libvirt APIs to get the data as I commented in patch set 7, and we will interact with qga directly through the socket file on the host. 

That simply isn't going to work. Libvirt will own any connection to the agent. Even if the socket is exposed on the host, you can't have a second process connecting to it - QEMU will only allow one process to use it. Anything you want todo with the QEMU guest agent will have to go via libvirt.

> but I think qga will be useful for grace shutdown, VM heartbeat and aslo cloud monitor project like ceilometer, I will try to add grace shutdown operation and os-status of instance(which means the OS of VM is active or not, currently the ACTIVE just meanning the VM is booting on the host, the os is not 'ACTIVE') to nova.

Looking more closely, I see that Nova already makes use of the dom.shutdown() API call todo graceful shutdown, so adding the agent will already do something useful, with that existing usage."}, {'account_id': 2711, 'date': '2013-08-02 13:03:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I'll try to implement my cloud monitor based libvirt_qemu+qga."}, {'account_id': 8467, 'date': '2013-08-13 10:37:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

[{'created': '2013-07-10 01:11:34.000000000', 'message': 'Added unix type channel support for qemu/kvm

Implements blueprint unix-virtio-serial-support
Currently nova supports pty type virtio-serial, this is not so convenient
and easy to use compared with unix socket type, we can use unix socket
type virtio-serial to interact with kvm guest(by qemu-guest-agent or
other agent like it), then we can get guest info on the compute node by
read/write the socket file(using qmp protocol), I think this is a useful
way to help us implement guest monitor in cloud environment.
DocImpact: please refer the page of bp

Change-Id: Ief70907add9ccd425a1594ab06c119256bdc89eb

commit_message:
Added qemu guest agent support for qemu/kvm

Currently nova doesn't support qemu-guest-agent or other agent like it
for kvm instance, if it is supported then we can get guest info on the
compute node through libvirt qemu extension api(qemuAgentCommand)
through guest agent, I think this is a useful way to help us to
interact with guest more directly and efficiently.
DocImpact: please refer the page of bp

Implements blueprint qemu-guest-agent-support
Change-Id: Ief70907add9ccd425a1594ab06c119256bdc89eb

commit_message:
Modified 3PAR drives to support 3parclient 2.0.0

Replaced ssh calls to remove host, show host,
show port, show vlun and create vlun with the
new hp3parclient calls.

Change-Id: I917b4263389331597103d2fe6c9a73994165051b
Fixes: bug #1211994

commit_message:
Always log stdout and stderr of CLI commands

Currently it was logged only when cli subprocess call itself
failed, so there was not enough debug output when asserts/test cases
failed.

Also stderr was logged only when it was merged to the stdout (almost
never).

Now we also don't have any use for check_output method anymore,
as cli.cmd() always captures the stderr,
whatever if for logging or merged into stdout for tests.

Also fixes invalid log.warning on newline at the end of ascii table.

Change-Id: I5251a06018e8bf79c30ad84f8f0ed8aac797f832

[{'created': '2013-08-28 20:33:31.000000000', 'message': "Remove base64 encoding feature from decrypted secrets GET API.

We are having issues supporting the base64 encoding feature when getting decrypted
secrets. In particular the Accept-Encoding http header appears to be overridden by
browsers such as Chrome and the 'requests' library used by Cloud Cafe, even though
'base64' is set for header. Rather than contend with this ill-supported header in the
long term, it is better to just remove this feature for the time being.

Change-Id: Iafafe364d273cd0ed6d5615729bdedce3c1335f5
Implements: blueprint api-secrets-remove-base64-support
"}]
commit_message:
Remove base64 encoding feature from decrypted secrets GET API.

We are having issues supporting the base64 encoding feature when getting decrypted
secrets. In particular the Accept-Encoding http header appears to be overridden by
browsers such as Chrome and the 'requests' library used by Cloud Cafe, even though
'base64' is set for header. Rather than contend with this ill-supported header in the
long term, it is better to just remove this feature for the time being.

Change-Id: Iafafe364d273cd0ed6d5615729bdedce3c1335f5
Implements: blueprint api-secrets-remove-base64-support

commit_message:
Don't eat callback exceptions

In order to properly ack(), reject() or requeue() messages
we need to preserve any exceptions thrown by the callbacks.

Change-Id: Icc7a38b69dc0812f94475530f5573342d92a6590

commit_message:
Use monkey_patch() in TestMigrationUtils setUp()

We use monkey patched sqlalchemy-migrate in
openstack.common.db.sqlalchemy.utils module. It allows us drop
unique constrains is SQLite.
If we run all tests, we also use `patched` migrate in
TestMigrationUtils(), but it patches in
`tests/unit/db/sqlalchemy/test_migrate.py` file. So tests from
TestMigrationUtils() class fails if we run them separately.

Added sqlalchemy-migrate monkey patch in setUp() method
TestMigrationUtils test class due to use `patched` migrate
in tests.

Fixes bug 1217306

Change-Id: I037ad36c1db3f88501f2b0f6ae9f2c946de1afa6

commit_message:
Replaces relative path to absolute path in conf file generator

The $OUTPUTFILE value is broken if the base-dir is passed as . or ..
This patch replaces relative paths to absolute paths passed to base-dir and
adds validation to $BASEDIR/$PACKAGENAME.

Fixes bug #1204204

Change-Id: Iaec57b0e9a2d53e7a601fe551e6ec4fd55da24b7

Clint, any reason not to have the default be higher?  I think Python's default recursion limit is on the order of 1000.  I can imagine a scenario where it would be fairly easy to have 3 nested stacks if folks start component-izing their stack resources to build on each other.  Any reason not to set the default config value at something on the order of 100?"}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-08-21 19:17:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

In parallel to this, I am working on some things to make the limitations on templates somewhat reasonable. My concern is that _an entire_ stack, including all nested stacks, must be kept in memory on the engine in order to do anything.

A 1MB template can have about 10000 nested stacks in it or about 9000 actual resources. So with 3 levels of depth and a 1MB template limitation, we are already allowing 100,000,000 1MB templates of real resources, so 900 billion actual resources. Basically each nesting level just blows open the numbers because of its exponential effect.

I think 512k would even be a reasonable template limitation, but that would just drop the numbers to 225 billion resources.

Now if we also clamp a total resource limit per stack (as in, the whole stack, not just per nested stack) and per tenant then more nesting levels will be a good idea. I'd be happy if that happened before this landed, and then we could raise the default nesting. In fact, now that I think about it, that is a more important limitation than this one."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-08-21 19:34:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Note that I opened this bug to track the resource limit:

[{'created': '2013-08-21 04:35:18.000000000', 'message': "Provide user control for maximum nesting depth

In the case of an infinitely recursing stack, Heat will continue to
keep nesting stacks until python's maximum stack recursion depth
is reached.  By this point a lot of memory and time may have been
spent parsing/loading/etc.

The default of 3 is enough to deploy a stack of stacks of stacks. It
can be raised by deployers if there is a desire to do larger and more
complicated stacks, at the cost of more resource utilization.

Fixes bug #1214239

Change-Id: Ic492ef84b94b1f715c49eef7e1794a486fb8182f

In the case of an infinitely recursing stack, Heat will continue to
keep nesting stacks until python's maximum stack recursion depth
is reached.  By this point a lot of memory and time may have been
spent parsing/loading/etc.

The default of 3 is enough to deploy a stack of stacks of stacks. It
can be raised by deployers if there is a desire to do larger and more
complicated stacks, at the cost of more resource utilization.

Also changing localhost references to RFC5737 TEST-NET-2 references to

commit_message:
Provide user control for maximum nesting depth

In the case of an infinitely recursing stack, Heat will continue to
keep nesting stacks until python's maximum stack recursion depth
is reached. By this point a lot of memory and time may have been
spent parsing/loading/etc.

The default of 3 is enough to deploy a stack of stacks of stacks. It
can be raised by deployers if there is a desire to do larger and more
complicated stacks, at the cost of more resource utilization.

Fixes bug #1214239

Change-Id: Ic492ef84b94b1f715c49eef7e1794a486fb8182f

commit_message:
Change localhost references in test_nested_stack

These references are using localhost which may be running a server and
provide valid responses, contaminating the test. Using RFC2606's
recommended test TLD of '.test' ensures that these will never resolve.

Change-Id: Ie555a321c2af23fbcf4aca9207acb6a0e40bb703

In run_tests.sh, function init_testr will initialize testr if the
directory .testrepository is not existed. Actually, testr will do
the check before run the test:

In Python package testrepository, setuptools_command.py:Testr.run

68 def run(self):
69     """Set up testr repo, then run testr"""

71         self._run_testr("init")

So, init_testr can be removed safely.

'}]
commit_message:
Don't need to init testr in run_tests.sh

In run_tests.sh, function init_testr will initialize testr if the
directory .testrepository is not existed. Actually, testr will do
the check before run the test:

In Python package testrepository, setuptools_command.py:Testr.run

68 def run(self):
69     """Set up testr repo, then run testr"""
70     if not os.path.isdir(".testrepository"):
71         self._run_testr("init")

So, init_testr can be removed safely.

Fixes Bug #1211098

Change-Id: I4bd2ef3dc107281892732efced268eb3b7c90cbb

commit_message:
Improve parameter related EC2 error codes

This patch replaces parameter/attribute related raises of EC2APIError
with specific exceptions.

 * Introduce new MissingParameter exception with 'MissingParameter'
   ec2_code.
 * Introduce new InvalidAttribute exception which isn't a valid EC2
   error code but it's needed nonetheless as the nova EC2 API isn't
   fully compatible.
 * Add 'InvalidParameterValue' ec2_code to existing
   InvalidParameterValue exception and use it where appropriate. Also
   add it to existing InvalidPortRange exception.

Implements: blueprint ec2-error-codes

Change-Id: I7820edfd9045fdc817a8538a754c9add20b68cf4

commit_message:
Port multiple_create extension to V3 API

Ports the multiple create extension to the V3 API. There is no part1
patch for this changeset because the original V2 file was just a stub
with all of the code in servers.py

DocImpact
Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I5eba468e9c4b753215b91607a3e2441626d2cb57

Hacking is referring to OpenStack Hacking, aka https://github.com/openstack-dev/hacking/blob/master/HACKING.rst

which is a flake8 plugin that checks for consistency with the OpenStack Hacking guidelines. 

Of course gating passed before and after this commit, because before all those checks were disabled.'}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2013-06-20 20:27:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-06-20 20:27:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

New patchset patch-id matches previous patchset, but commit message has changed.'}, {'account_id': 1216, 'date': '2013-06-20 20:44:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Yeah Sam, this the Hacking checks that OpenStack apparently decided on. How they decided on that I'm not sure. I don't remember voting. I don't remember anyone that works on Swift bringing this up and wanting it. Aside from that, I don't think I really have any problems with these particular changes though I do wonder why someone cares that much about minutiae on a project they don't even work on. :P"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-06-20 21:07:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

@Dirk: I wasn't clear before. Here's what I did:

- applied this patch
- ran tox: it passed
- reverted the whitespace changes in swift/account/reaper.py
- ran tox; it still passed
- reverted every change except tox.ini
- ran tox; it still passed

I'd have thought that the last 2 tox runs would have failed since I made the code not meet the new requirements, but they didn't. That's why I'm confused; there doesn't seem to be any enforcement of these things.

Note that these tox runs were performed on my SAIO, not any Jenkins thing."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-20 21:17:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

@sam i think you need to pip install hacking to actually test it, if it still passed did you regenerate your tox venv ? (basically rm -rf .tox and rerun tox).

In my opinion I think those checks improve the clarity in some cases (at least I don't have to git blame to see who put that TODO) but we probably want to discuss it first at for example the next openstack meeting before accepting this since this would be 'gated' by jenkins."}, {'account_id': 1216, 'date': '2013-06-20 21:47:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Sam, try something like this:

    $ cd
    $ git clone https://github.com/openstack-dev/hacking.git
    $ cd hacking
    $ sudo python setup.py develop
    $ cd ~/swift
    $ time flake8 swift
    swift/__init__.py:1:1: H102  Apache 2.0 license header not found
    import gettext
    ^
    swift/proxy/controllers/__init__.py:1:1: H102  Apache 2.0 license header not found
    from swift.proxy.controllers.base import Controller
    ^

    real    0m17.563s
    user    0m0.830s
    sys     0m16.730s

:)'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-06-20 23:29:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

So, if I add "hacking==0.5.5" to test-requirements.txt, then rebuild tox environments, it works.

If we want this (and that is a very large "if"), then "hacking" needs to be added as a test requirement. Otherwise, Jenkins is going to start rejecting submissions that pass local tox runs, and the rejections will be for trivia. That'll get real old, real fast.'}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2013-06-21 09:00:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks for figuring that out. I'll update test-requirements.txt in the next version of the patch. 

I was under the assumption that Swift is a normal OpenStack project that follows the general conventions, so I went ahead and fixed the same swoop of stuff that I did for the other projects as well."}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2013-06-21 09:01:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-21 09:45:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Start using Hacking

Instead of blacklisting Hacking globally,
only blacklist those that currently occur frequently
(for a later followup patch), and fix the rest. In
detail:

H101  Use TODO(NAME)
H201  no 'except:' at least use 'except Exception:'
H231  octal number 022 should be written as 0o22
H401  docstring should not start with a space
H701  Empty localization string

Change-Id: Ib3b3d56b68d1cf15d3b67ac9749fcbdb876dc52a

commit_message:
dump keystoneclient output if table label is None

I haven't been able to reproduce the referenced bug, so this assertion
will anticipate the failure condition (svc['__label'] is None) and dump
the raw output to assist in debugging.

Related-Bug: 1217159
Change-Id: I1b345ff68384581a4cc37f06b2abf7e5b18745f4

commit_message:
Migrate manage script needs import of db session module

This import looks like it is not used but importing this module as
the side effect of defining the olso configuration. Without it the
script will not work.

Change-Id: Id65f726f34aa2fb86fda13fd65e2e512b3a899ac

commit_message:
Raises masked AssertionError in _test_network_api

The _test_network_api method was catching an AssertionError to do some
more checking but failed to raise the original error if the checking
didn't hit any matches. This patch fixes the test to raise the original
assertion error.

Closes-Bug: #1212017

Change-Id: I33147d18e33cd4babfc3f5cb572007bc7e4c07e6

commit_message:
Fix field attributes based on form data via YAQL expression.

If there is no form data gathered yet, field attribute specified by YAQL expression
will yield default field attribute value (from field.__dict__) instead of False
value.

Change-Id: Ie74f5a48ce90e3dab33cd3fc8b57a366433d7fe5
Fixes: bug MRN-852.

commit_message:
Object support for instance groups

The patch set adds object support to the instance groups.
This is required for: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/30028/

This is part of the blueprint instance-group-api-extension.

Change-Id: I599016b7a15d6045ae5129352eacc60a37ac7106

commit_message:
use 'exc_info=True' instead of import traceback

We need store traceback message in log sometime. Python logging module
already provide a argument to do that. For example, we could:

logger.error('msg', exc_info=True) # log current exc_info
logger.debug(e, exc_info=(type_,value_,tb)) # log exc_info passed in arg
logger.exception('msg') # exception add exc_info automaticly

There're many places using traceback, but only two places are using
traceback for loging exc_info. (some use to store into variable, some in
openstack/common leave this to oslo)

Change-Id: I96eff1e7a0437c358753e636a8a6ac860074cb25

commit_message:
Don't fidget with the image/snapshot name/size if it's set

Principle of Least Surprise: don't "help" users by setting field
names if they've already set them to something.  So if they've set
the volume name already, leave it alone.  If they've set the size
to something at least as large as what the source image/snapshot
requires, also leave it alone.

This means that if users are flipping through the available
images/snapshots, the UI will auto-set the values at most once.
This seems to be a workable trade-off as far as usability goes.

Fixes Bug: 1215566

Change-Id: I02c5ec0df1895ecaa24843712b9346ac0e588f59

commit_message:
Enable the scaling up of nodes in a cluster

Enabled the ability to add nodes to a cluster.  The ability to delete
nodes will be added in a future commit once Ambari supports the
deletion of hosts from a cluster.

Fixes: bug #1216088

Change-Id: I5bd5bf1b55412fbebbc5d9eb84cccc57e4b1824c

need to register the system log in to rhn and subscribe to an
available subscription.

export RHSM_PASSWORD to your rhn password

To get the qcow2 image, log into rhn.redhat.com and download the
image from

"}, {'created': '2013-08-18 01:38:41.000000000', 'message': "Adding rhel installation element

Adding RHEL support for partitioning

RHEL 6 doesn't create /dev/loop*p* devices for partitions. It does
use device mapper to create the device under /dev/mapper/loop*p*.

This patch adds a common functioon to figure out what operating
system disk image builder is being run on, then decides where to look
for the loop partition.

Change-Id: Idb547f4ffe75514b1e3f6b34f5f347493b132925

 RHEL 6 doesn't create /dev/loop*p* devices for partitions. It does

commit_message:
Add rhel installation element

If you want to have the installation update packages, you'll
need to register the system log in to rhn and subscribe to an
available subscription.
export DIB_RHSM_USER to your rhn username
export DIB_RHSM_PASSWORD to your rhn password

To get the qcow2 image, log into rhn.redhat.com and download the
image from
https://rhn.redhat.com/rhn/software/channel/downloads/Download.do?cid=16952
Then export DIB_CLOUD_IMAGES to whereever you're hosting the qcow2.

Change-Id: Idb547f4ffe75514b1e3f6b34f5f347493b132925

commit_message:
Avoid performing extra query for fetching mac learning binding

Bug 1214879

Add a relationship performing eager load in the Port model, thus preventing
the 'extend' function from performing an extra query.
This patch also replaces assertTrue with assertEqual in unit tests as it
needs to evaluate whether the value of the mac_learning_enabled attribute
is equal to the boolean literal True, whereas assertTrue verifies that the
expression passed to it evaluates to True. This means that any value but
False will be enough for the test to pass, which is not correct.

Change-Id: I03345ef3a125fdfa1ec7f6c3363d76efc12ced82

commit_message:
Allow for skipping admin roles loading on context creation

Bug 1216866

There are cases in which an admin context is created only to grab a db
session and ensure no tenant filters are applied in _model_query. In
these cases evaluating the policy engine for grabbing admin roles is not
necessary, and can cause unexpected and serious issues if the context is
grabbed before all the extensions are loaded.

Change-Id: I0cbf4b51ca1286373c16eb907840a32f4b8190c6

commit_message:
add audit middleware

add audit middleware which appends open standard audit information
to the request environ and sends notifications using
middleware.notifier

blueprint support-standard-audit-formats

Change-Id: Ie67cf4a76ed5e177cdbb93a4c919a6ddf06ae49f

commit_message:
fix volume swap exception cases

Currently when the target instance id doesn't match with the instance_id of the
volume to be replaced VolumeUnattached is raised, and InvalidVolume would be a
fittest response.
In the other hand, currently, when the volme to be replaced is not attached at
all InvalidVolume is raised, and VolumeUnnatached would be a fittest response.

Change-Id: I661b97762af70765ab8111313d24cf1a175f7e6c

commit_message:
Add option --min-tmpfs <size> to disk-image-create

In some scenarios, the required space in the tmpfs partition can be
larger (or smaller) than the default one, producing errors due to
the lack of enough space (or performance penalties for not using
tmpfs).

Using --min-tmpfs <size>, we can hint the working set size we'll need
and let dib choose to avoid or use tmpfs.

Change-Id: I7d5fe498302a100c8555ae542268e14b21f3a0c5

commit_message:
Combine compress and save image into one function

When compressing an image, this is done in the same dir where the raw
image resides, doubling the amount of space needed (scarce when
using tmpfs), and then it's moved to the .cache folder in disk.

Combining these two functions, we reduce the amount of space needed
in the tmpfs partition (when in use), and the compressed image is
created directly on the .cache folder disk, so there is no need to
move the compressed image after the process into disk.

Change-Id: I451d24bdd6fa0983414244135dff5e96c0549833
