commit_message:
Fix useless assertTrue

In glance/tests/functional/test_scrubber.py,
TestScrubber::test_scrubber_with_metadata_enc(), local var marker_uri
is always not None, so self.assertTrue(marker_uri is not None) don't
make sense. This patch init it with None.

Change-Id: Id2fcffe6ff67b6fa59247d42ab15ffb228dd622f

1) instance.pci_devices can be None, but code to convert the pci_devices

commit_message:
Fix Instance object issues

1) instance.pci_devices can be None, but code to convert the pci_devices
joined 'column' on a sqlalchemy Instance model bombs when this is true.

2) When sending the Instance object over RPC with a None pci_devices
field, a deserialization error occurs because of not properly accounting
for None.

3) In tests, pci_devices is set for db.instance_create(), but
instance_create() does not support creating the PciDevice models.

4) The Instance object code assumes 'pci_devices' is joined by default
when it is not.  This shows up as a problem in compute tests in later
patchsets of mine that need to convert sqlalchemy Instance models to
Instance objects using INSTANCE_DEFAULT_FIELDS.  It also happens that
'fault' should not be a default field as it is never actually joined.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I16fae96b7b9ba17d339bbd589ecc75465f5f56be

commit_message:
Add env to make_subprocess

Due to a previous commit, a client of make_subprocess is making a call
with an env parameter. As make_subprocess does not have such a
parameter, image upload fails. This patch adds the env keyword argument
to make_subprocess, and use that in the Popen call.

Fixes bug 1216267

'}, {'created': '2013-07-30 16:33:03.000000000', 'message': 'Add defense for useid==None in ldap backends

Add defense in assignment.backends.ldap.Assignment::_get_metadata(),
return empty dict rather than throw exception when userid==None.

commit_message:
Add defense in ldap:get_roles_for_user_and_project

LDAP:get_roles_for_user_and_project will raise "Could not find user"
exception when you try to get roles by user(user was in a group) and
project.

In this patch:
1. Add defense in assignment.backends.ldap.Assignment::_get_metadata(),
return empty dict rather than throw exception when userid==None or
tenantid==None.
2. Remove checking existance of tenant_id and user_id
logic, because these logics were always done before this method being
called.
3. Add testcase test_get_role_by_user_and_project_with_user_in_group
in test_backend module.

Fixes bug #1204221

Change-Id: I68c39afddde4065fc61ffb9451592c5108dc138b

commit_message:
Minimize ovs l2 agent calls to get_vif_port_set()

The ovs l2 agent was previously calling get_vif_port_set() on the
integration bridge once per rpc_loop() iteration and then again in
the periodic _report_state() call that returns the current device
count to the neutron service.  Since get_vif_port_set() is an
expensive call (relying on shell commands) and since there
is minimal risk associated with reporting stats that are a few
seconds old, this patch caches the device count for reuse by
_report_state().

Partial-Bug: 1177973

Change-Id: Ice73384ed1ba1e97120028cd0a9bff94a62a41a4

commit_message:
Remove trailing comma

Closes-Bug: #1217135

There are trailing commas in default value of some options, uncomment
them will cause CRITICAL error for neutron-server. These sample config
may mislead operators, so this patch fix them to the correct format.

commit_message:
PCI alias support

Add PCI alias support.

User may have specific device requirements for passthrough device, like
specific NIC card from specific vendor with specific network access.

It's too long and not straightforward to specify these requirements in
flavor directly, also cloud administrator may want to control what pci
requirements the user can specify and want to hide some device details
like the switch IP address a NIC is connected.

Pci alias is defined to specify the pci requirements and is specified in
the flavor extra specs. The API layer will translate the alias information
in flavor extra specs to pci requirement according to pci alias definition.

bp:pci-passthrough-base

Change-Id:I82a7826f72da8b41e95fb6d27cd03f68ed849880
Signed-off-by: Yongli He <yongli.he@intel.com>
Signed-off-by: Yunhong Jiang <yunhong.jiang@intel.com>

commit_message:
Add PCI stats

PCI stats abstract the pci device info on compute node for scheduler.
provide better performance than join load from pci device table.

PCI stats contain the available count info for PCI devices with same
spec, ie, the same product_id and verndor_id.and provide method to check
if the requests is supported.

bp:pci-passthrough-base

Change-Id: I8d77c685f774aae22da87be9e822bfd44f0b7a6d
Signed-off-by: Yunhong Jiang <yunhong.jiang@intel.com>
Signed-off-by: Yongli He <yongli.he@intel.com>

commit_message:
Add the api config opts in groups to deal with the single heat.conf

So first off, I also don't like the replicating of the api_opts in wsgi.py
but if I don't do that the sample generator doesn't work:(

We add the wsgi options into a group for each of the api servers with
the deprecated group of "DEFAULT" so it still deals with the flat layout.

The behaviour is as follows (assuming heat-api):
1) if you have both (/etc/heat/{heat.conf, heat-api.conf}
   the value in heat-api.conf wins over heat.conf
2) if you have just one of the config files but a value in both the
   [DEFAULT] section and the [heat-api] section then the value in heat-api
   wins.

bug #1209141
Change-Id: I66ddb3dca91d13b28e68dfb4306e94eb4e537fa7

commit_message:
Assignment to reserved built-in symbol: help

In file tools/install_venv.py, print_help(), built-in symbol help
was re-assignment as local vars, it is easily lead to a
misunderstanding, so rename them.
This patch do not modify any functionality.

Change-Id: Iaae88b9e5e9f89af67e15532847ea2e9f2c63b6f

commit_message:
Make xenapi capabilities['enabled'] use service enabled

filters.compute_filter is enabled by default along with libvirt, but the
capabilities['enabled'] section of it is only supported by XenAPI.
This used to work by adding a parameter to capabilities, but since
the capabilities RPC is being removed, use conductor.service_update to tell
the scheduler which host is disabled.

service_update is already the way to tell the scheduler about other
disabled hosts, so to keep backwards compatibility keep host_enabled but
use service_update underneath.

Part of bp no-compute-fanout-to-scheduler

Change-Id: Ica1919cfe9a2402b2107c557c10d47e01a6c430b

"}, {'created': '2013-08-17 11:02:48.000000000', 'message': 'Keystone Caching Layer for Manager Calls

Implements core elements of Keystone Caching layer. dogpile.cache
is used as the caching library to provide flexibility to the cache
backend (out of the box, Redis, Memcached, File, and in-Memory).

The keystone.common.cache.on_arguments decorator is used cache the
return value of method and functions that are meant to be cached.

This patchset inclues basic Token caching as the first implemntation
of this caching layer.  The following methods are cached:
    * token_api.get_token,
    * token_api.list_revoked_tokens
    * token_provider_api.validate_v3_token
    * token_provider_api.check_v3_token

Calls to token_api.delete_token and token_api.delete_tokens will
properly invalidate the cache for the tokens being acted upon, as
well as invalidating the cache for the revoked_tokens_list.

The default behavior is to not cache anything (using a no-op cacher).

developing.rst has been updated to give an outline on how to approach
adding the caching layer onto a manager object.

Subsequent patches will build upon this code to enable caching across
much of the rest of the Keystone drivers.

DocImpact

partial-blueprint: caching-layer-for-driver-calls

Change-Id: I664ddccd8d1d393cf50d24054f946512093fb790

Implements core elements of Keystone Caching layer. dogpile.cache

This patchset inclues basic Token caching as the first implemntation
of this caching layer.  The following methods are cached:
    * token_api.get_token,
    * token_api.list_revoked_tokens
    * token_provider_api.validate_v3_token
    * token_provider_api.check_v3_token

Calls to token_api.delete_token and token_api.delete_tokens will
properly invalidate the cache for the tokens being acted upon, as
well as invalidating the cache for the revoked_tokens_list.

The default behavior is to not cache anything (using a no-op cacher).

commit_message:
Keystone Caching Layer for Manager Calls

Implements core elements of Keystone Caching layer. dogpile.cache
is used as the caching library to provide flexibility to the cache
backend (out of the box, Redis, Memcached, File, and in-Memory).

The keystone.common.cache.on_arguments decorator is used cache the
return value of method and functions that are meant to be cached.

The default behavior is to not cache anything (using a no-op cacher).

developing.rst has been updated to give an outline on how to approach
adding the caching layer onto a manager object.

Subsequent patches will build upon this code to enable caching across
the various keystone subsystems.

DocImpact

partial-blueprint: caching-layer-for-driver-calls
Change-Id: I664ddccd8d1d393cf50d24054f946512093fb790

Fixes: bug MRN-856.

commit_message:
Import is_service_enabled from module

An additional step for H302, and needed here to make mocking
is_service_enabled across modules more consistent and easier
(e.g. mocking only one signature as opposed to both
api.base.is_service_enabled and quotas.is_service_enabled).

Partial-Bug: #1109140

Change-Id: Ie6cec3138de6f2fc57b68e90db45f53bb94ab87d

commit_message:
Revert "image-delete fires multiple queries to delete its child entries"

This reverts commit c7e9786aa777eb6a44a9b9350da587546c347c7a.

This commit effectively breaks the ability to delete glance images
on Fedora 19.

Fixes LP Bug #1216102.

Change-Id: I5c5a06672a7c4a98d6f7954ec0079d39aeb8800a

commit_message:
Write to /dev/vdb, not /dev/null

context, it seems clear the writes should be happening to /dev/vdb
instead.

commit_message:
xenapi: refactor - extract image_utils

Extract GlanceImage and RawImage. With these abstractions in place, it's
much more easier to implement support for new container and image
formats.

related to blueprint xenapi-supported-image-import-export

Change-Id: Id48d9d92e59c4ae9190b5d17a22ad8405114269a

commit_message:
Add support for heat enviroments

heat now has global environments that make it easy
to rename and customise resource behaviour. These
are yaml files that need to be in /etc/heat/environment.d/

Change-Id: I5a08c6ce8f5d7222f79aab2be0903ba783c10aa1

Add default auth_uri setting for auth token.

The latest keystoneclient code now gives a Warning if auth_uri
isn't explicitly specified.

commit_message:
Remove _expire_reservations from periodic tasks

if the scheduler hasn't done anything for the past few minutes there is no
reason to keep running this task. Instead it can be restarted upon the
next scheduling event.

Fix bug 1212028

Change-Id: Ib4eb74a79e6c7566fbfd2a563804a1e761dca4e7

commit_message:
removes self.fail as suggested by HACKING.rst

removes every occurrence of self.fail as per HACKING.rst file; it
is either replaced with a LOG+raise or removed completely when not
needed (again, HACKING.rst suggests the try clause should be avoided
too letting the original exception to flow).

Change-Id: Ief779bada1aa53837d62e3f58a7d3418eef494ba
Implements: blueprint replace-self-fail

[{'created': '2013-08-14 19:44:13.000000000', 'message': 'Adds support for the Hyper-V WMI V2 namespace

Blueprint: hyper-v-wmi-v2

The Hyper-V APIs are mainly based on WMI. The original 2008 Hyper-V
release introduced the "root\virtualization" namespace which got
superseded in Hyper-V Server / Windows Server 2012 by the
"root\virtualization\v2" namespace (referred as V2 in the sources).

The original namespace has been dropped in the upcoming Hyper-V 2012
R2 (currently available in preview), which means that the Grizzly code
will not be compatible with it as is.

The Hyper-V driver is structured with a clear decoupling between OS
interaction classes (so called *utils modules and classes) and the
agent's logic.

This allows us to provide an implementation of the V2 API without
impacting the rest of the agent's code, based on a factory module
added to instantiate the proper version of the *utils classes: the
original "V1" ones for versions of the OS predating 2012 and the
newer "V2" ones starting from Hyper-V 2012 (Windows kernel version
6.2).

commit_message:
Adds support for the Hyper-V WMI V2 namespace

Blueprint: hyper-v-wmi-v2

The Hyper-V APIs are mainly based on WMI. The original 2008 Hyper-V
release introduced the "root\virtualization" namespace which got
superseded in Hyper-V Server / Windows Server 2012 by the
"root\virtualization\v2" namespace (referred as V2 in the sources).

The original namespace has been dropped in the upcoming Hyper-V 2012
R2 (currently available in preview), which means that the Grizzly code
will not be compatible with it as is.

The Hyper-V driver is structured with a clear decoupling between OS
interaction classes (so called *utils modules and classes) and the
agent's logic.

This allows us to provide an implementation of the V2 API without
impacting the rest of the agent's code, based on a factory module
added to instantiate the proper version of the *utils classes: the
original "V1" ones for versions of the OS predating 2012 and the
newer "V2" ones starting from Hyper-V 2012 (Windows kernel version
6.2).

Change-Id: I380d8c65715242d8a5b94b5061ebe4f30e6c2090

commit_message:
pin keyring to < 2.0

keyring 2.0.0 (released aug 18, 2013) contains a regression on ubuntu
regarding GnomeKeyring, see comment #5 by Pavel on:

    https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/python-keyring/+bug/1197988

adding bounds to pytz to mirror master so pip can resolve pytz in a sane way.
(required for requirements-install test to succeed)

Change-Id: I3320da4f13cded498d6622525d56c31ae9936e0f
Closes-Bug: 1193164

commit_message:
Remove excessive YAQL check for multi-instance services.

It is mandatory for dcInstances in such services to be >= 2, so checking
it is redundant.

Change-Id: I2c1e5e156bba1c4c4ed1cd5fb643410c24055706
Fixes: bug MRN-853.

commit_message:
Allow generator as input to utils.print_list.

Once the table is built, the length of the prettytable's internal array
is checked rather than re-iterrating over the input.

Adds tests for utils.print_list with list and generator input.

Fixes bug: #986987
Upsream LP: #1180059
Cheery-Picked: 95e142a1738cc01a84de427a7c96435a5b01cbf3

Change-Id: I1265bf83c2a9d94f63b5da9a8c1a8b64f218235a

commit_message:
Apply a tempate filter to output for openrc.sh

When special characters are used in tenant names, horizon escapes them
when generating openrc.sh for example & is written as &

Change-Id: I3fbb6c66c6ccc09ad48eb224e26ab9851191bb46
Fixes: bug #1100042

[{'created': '2013-08-27 05:31:44.000000000', 'message': 'Make logical_resource_id renaming backward compatible

The rename of logical_resource_id to resource_name changed the
return value of resource and event API. Adding a redundant
logical_resource_id back to make the change backward compatible.

Change-Id: I08ab00e38bae6e9bbaf8387dc01effaf776d0b3c
'}]
commit_message:
Make logical_resource_id renaming backward compatible

The rename of logical_resource_id to resource_name changed the
return value of resource and event API. Adding a redundant
logical_resource_id back to make the change backward compatible.

Change-Id: I08ab00e38bae6e9bbaf8387dc01effaf776d0b3c

commit_message:
Add unittest framework + tests for wrapper scripts

This commit adds a framework for running unittests on tempest to
verify that tempest works as expect. The first tests added are to
verify the response codes of the test runner wrapper scripts we use
on jenkins jobs.

Change-Id: If8e91238054593999e7b5bc34da499bd0ac02311

@markwash, below is the "mysql explain" per your request.

mysql> explain SELECT anon_1.anon_2_images_created_at AS anon_1_anon_2_images_created_at, anon_1.anon_2_images_updated_at AS anon_1_anon_2_images_updated_at, anon_1.anon_2_images_deleted_at AS anon_1_anon_2_images_deleted_at, anon_1.anon_2_images_deleted AS anon_1_anon_2_images_deleted, anon_1.anon_2_images_id AS anon_1_anon_2_images_id, anon_1.anon_2_images_name AS anon_1_anon_2_images_name, anon_1.anon_2_images_disk_format AS anon_1_anon_2_images_disk_format, anon_1.anon_2_images_container_format AS anon_1_anon_2_images_container_format, anon_1.anon_2_images_size AS anon_1_anon_2_images_size, anon_1.anon_2_images_status AS anon_1_anon_2_images_status, anon_1.anon_2_images_is_public AS anon_1_anon_2_images_is_public, anon_1.anon_2_images_checksum AS anon_1_anon_2_images_checksum, anon_1.anon_2_images_min_disk AS anon_1_anon_2_images_min_disk, anon_1.anon_2_images_min_ram AS anon_1_anon_2_images_min_ram, anon_1.anon_2_images_owner AS anon_1_anon_2_images_owner, anon_1.anon_2_images_protected AS anon_1_anon_2_images_protected, image_locations_1.created_at AS image_locations_1_created_at, image_locations_1.updated_at AS image_locations_1_updated_at, image_locations_1.deleted_at AS image_locations_1_deleted_at, image_locations_1.deleted AS image_locations_1_deleted, image_locations_1.id AS image_locations_1_id, image_locations_1.image_id AS image_locations_1_image_id, image_locations_1.value AS image_locations_1_value, image_locations_1.meta_data AS image_locations_1_meta_data, image_properties_1.created_at AS image_properties_1_created_at, image_properties_1.updated_at AS image_properties_1_updated_at, image_properties_1.deleted_at AS image_properties_1_deleted_at, image_properties_1.deleted AS image_properties_1_deleted, image_properties_1.id AS image_properties_1_id, image_properties_1.image_id AS image_properties_1_image_id, image_properties_1.name AS image_properties_1_name, image_properties_1.value AS image_properties_1_value FROM (SELECT anon_2.images_created_at AS anon_2_images_created_at, anon_2.images_updated_at AS anon_2_images_updated_at, anon_2.images_deleted_at AS anon_2_images_deleted_at, anon_2.images_deleted AS anon_2_images_deleted, anon_2.images_id AS anon_2_images_id, anon_2.images_name AS anon_2_images_name, anon_2.images_disk_format AS anon_2_images_disk_format, anon_2.images_container_format AS anon_2_images_container_format, anon_2.images_size AS anon_2_images_size, anon_2.images_status AS anon_2_images_status, anon_2.images_is_public AS anon_2_images_is_public, anon_2.images_checksum AS anon_2_images_checksum, anon_2.images_min_disk AS anon_2_images_min_disk, anon_2.images_min_ram AS anon_2_images_min_ram, anon_2.images_owner AS anon_2_images_owner, anon_2.images_protected AS anon_2_images_protected FROM (SELECT images.created_at AS images_created_at, images.updated_at AS images_updated_at, images.deleted_at AS images_deleted_at, images.deleted AS images_deleted, images.id AS images_id, images.name AS images_name, images.disk_format AS images_disk_format, images.container_format AS images_container_format, images.size AS images_size, images.status AS images_status, images.is_public AS images_is_public, images.checksum AS images_checksum, images.min_disk AS images_min_disk, images.min_ram AS images_min_ram, images.owner AS images_owner, images.protected AS images_protected FROM images UNION SELECT images.created_at AS images_created_at, images.updated_at AS images_updated_at, images.deleted_at AS images_deleted_at, images.deleted AS images_deleted, images.id AS images_id, images.name AS images_name, images.disk_format AS images_disk_format, images.container_format AS images_container_format, images.size AS images_size, images.status AS images_status, images.is_public AS images_is_public, images.checksum AS images_checksum, images.min_disk AS images_min_disk, images.min_ram AS images_min_ram, images.owner AS images_owner, images.protected AS images_protected FROM images INNER JOIN image_members ON images.id = image_members.image_id) AS anon_2 WHERE anon_2.images_deleted = 0 AND anon_2.images_status != '' AND (EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM image_tags WHERE anon_2.images_id = commit_message:
Implement image query by tag

Sometimes, user want to query images by tag since it's an
intuitive way to distinct different image. The REST API
would be like: v2/images?tag=x86&tag=64bit

docImpact
Implement bp image-query-by-tag

Change-Id: I42946fa838ed896823e17fd4c51995209d9d2ad3

commit_message:
Add optimized volume migration to Storwize/SVC

Add an optimized migration path for when the source and destination are
managed by the same storage. If the source and destination pools have
the same extent_size, it will use the optimal migratevdisk command.
Otherwise, it will use addvdiskcopy and rmvdiskcopy, which must be
watched until the copies are sync'ed.

Change-Id: Ic6069422f5ac7f963f4b1268c0d632a038a8474f

commit_message:
Fix cinder error for deprecated Netapp drivers

We deprecated some NetApp drivers in
this release. This change fixes c-vol
breakdown in case of cinder configured for
deprecated drivers and helps
in upgrade scenarios between releases
by printing appropriate warning and
suggestion message for deprecated drivers.

bug 1217220

Change-Id: I533d42257d93f706303b475fb4f222adcc0df3ed

[{'created': '2013-08-23 10:32:57.000000000', 'message': "Remove unnecessary aws_* from user_creds

We currently store aws_creds, but it's never used in any of the clients
which consume the stored context, so it makes sense to remove it from the
DB, but leave it in heat/common/context.py, so the credentials used for
real requests *to* heat (authenticated via the ec2token middleware) are
obtainable in the context, but we don't populate them in context to be
used in client conntections for  requests going *from* heat.

Fixes bug #1215850

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary aws_* from user_creds

We currently store aws_creds, but it's never used in any of the clients
which consume the stored context.  It makes sense to remove it from the
DB, but leave it in heat/common/context.py; then the credentials used for
real requests *to* heat (authenticated via the ec2token middleware) are
obtainable in the context, but we don't populate them in context to be
used in client connections for requests going *from* heat.

Fixes bug #1215850

Change-Id: I7a75c70beb0318a1e83ac0ab45d13802999d1282

Remove unused service_* columns from user_creds

The service_user and service_password columns are not used anywhere
so remove the columns from the DB and the model

bug #1215850

commit_message:
Update availability_zone on time if it was changed

The problem is that when the availability_zones for one host
aggregation was updated, the VM attribute of availability_zones
which belong to the host in the availability_zones was
not updated on time.

If updated values include availability_zones, then the cache
which stored availability_zones and host need to be reset.

Fix bug 1203250

Change-Id: Ib3f08fbe3c74d5aa101da78faed43b0bc03cb988

'}, {'created': '2013-06-28 00:56:46.000000000', 'message': 'Project to Endpoint association for catalog filtering

Implemented CRUD API to associate projects with
endpoints. Every single endpoint in the catalog can
now be associated with a project.

This allows the token validation and request to sport
only the endpoints that are associated to the project
when the token request is scoped.

If this feature is not used, meaning no endpoints are
associated with a project, the full catalog is presented
as response to the token request.
This ensures backward compatibility with the 3.0 behaviour

blueprint endpoint-filtering

Change-Id: Idaa7f448a67e3bae01ba12686be37ba058183cf6

commit_message:
Create associations between projects and endpoints

OS-EP-FILTER Implementation

There are new methods to create endpoint and project associations.
A full CRUD API to assign projects to endpoints as well as
the ability to check all the projects associated with a given
endpoint.

The association is used to pick what endpoints are visible
for the given project and a filtered catalog is built
accordingly.

During a project-scoped token request, if project-endpoint
associations have been created, the returned catalog will only
list the project linked endpoints.

blueprint endpoint-filtering

Change-Id: Idaa7f448a67e3bae01ba12686be37ba058183cf6

commit_message:
BigSwitch plugin - add portbinding info in requests to controller

Include portbinding info in requests to controller so it receives
information about the compute node like the VIF type and the host
ID. Also includes better debug output on back-end failures.

Fixes: bug #1216061
Change-Id: Ib85c8a088ee9fb94baaf8f28849b318b32d9d672

commit_message:
Make Neutron NVP plugin future-versions friendly

This patch enables the plugin to deal correctly with
newer versions of the NVP platform; this is done by
allowing the plugin to fall back to the closest known
version of the NVP platform. This is acceptable behavior
as L2/L3 operations implemented by the platform are most
certainly backward compatible.

This patch also improves test coverage for this part of the
code, which is critical to the correct behavior of the plugin.

Fixes bug #1217479

Change-Id: Ifcce47c6ee2bc2bc96ddfe9298d252700aceca3f

'}, {'created': '2013-08-13 14:34:23.000000000', 'message': 'Fixing erroneous clearing of test callstack

This modification addresses Bug #1210292, specifically addressing
the case where the test framework callstack is cleared when no
asserts are raised in assert_called_anytime. This test method
verifies that a specific API method call was made at any time
during a test. If a test makes multiple calls to this method, and

commit_message:
Fixing erroneous clearing of test callstack

This modification addresses Bug #1210292, specifically addressing
the case where the test framework callstack is cleared when no
asserts are raised in assert_called_anytime. This test method
verifies that a specific API method call was made at any time
during a test. If a test makes multiple calls to this method, and
the first call yields no assertions, the subsequent calls will fail
because the first assert in the method verifies that the callstack
is non-empty. The error itself likely exists because
assert_called_anytime is not currently used in the
python-cinderclient testing framework.

The fix involves deleting the last line in the method that clears
the callstack.

Fixes: bug 1210292

Change-Id: I8b7b740957841a328b2f0ca888190f758cbdd234

commit_message:
Add update_snapshot_metadata action

This allows Nova to update the state and progress of a snapshot that
it is manipulating.

Also fix formatting bug in AssertionError in post_snapshots_1234_action.

Implements blueprint qemu-assisted-snapshots

Change-Id: Ia108e14870410b783c5d074db89acb94e83fce99

Please do the following:

1.  Break this up into smaller patches.  The code from common can be merged down in a stand alone patch.

2.  Move the common auth code from Oslo to Keystone.  Keystone is going to be the authentication library for the other clients, and the code should live in the Keystone client

3.  Avoid the renames in this patch, as it needlessly expands the line count.


4.  In general, don't delete tests in the same commit as one that makes changes.  It is too easy to hide a regression."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-07 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Abandoned

commit_message:
Use apiclient library

This library can be used in novaclient, keystoneclient,
glanceclient, and other client projects. The library
contains common code and uses python-requests for
HTTP communication.

Features:
* share one authentication result between sessions with
  several servers (good for horizon and python-openstackclient);
* reissue authentication request for expired tokens;
* pluggable authentication;
* rich exceptions hierarchy.

Partially implements: blueprint common-client-library

Change-Id: I9155613f012d7372b8a11e0950ac450b31a8c173

commit_message:
Use wheel by default

The wheel format is the new binary format for python packaging. If a
wheel is available, it's always a thing you want to use instead of a
source tarball. pbr will support these by providing the PIP_USE_WHEEL
environment variable to pip commands it runs. If pip >= 1.4 is
installed, this will tell it to try to use wheels.

Change-Id: I554510ee41109ba0167e92fb7b47f57f9bbcd931

commit_message:
Adds the missing [keystone_authtoken] directives

This patch adds the missing [keystone_authtoken] section in the
ceilometer.conf.sample file, by patching the generator script
tools/conf/generate_sample.sh, which was modified to also read the
keystone.middleware.auth_token module and extract things from there.
Also, fixes a generator.py crash when there's no help text defined.

Fixes Bug1177443

Change-Id: Ic5f52aa205d0dc8188a5bf569622cd0a36662fdd

commit_message:
Removing redundant operations on Expirer

Remove the redundant calls to the object server, when the
expirer calls delete_object to delete expired objects in
the .expiring_objects_account.

Change-Id: If3c553fc9a241e9db6ed6ec43cc67537c1471609
Fixes: bug #1076202

@peter True, the behavior can change if you have multiple if- headers set.  I'll check the RFC to see if I can figure out who should win.  Hopefully that's defined."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-08-15 00:50:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

From RFC 2616 section 9.3 ("GET"):

    The semantics of the GET method change to a "conditional GET" if the
    request message includes an If-Modified-Since, If-Unmodified-Since,
    If-Match, If-None-Match, or If-Range header field. A conditional GET
    method requests that the entity be transferred only under the
    circumstances described by the conditional header field(s).

So, if a client sends If-Modified-Since *and* If-None-Match, then it looks like we have to pay attention to both of those and only send back a 304 if they both match.

I *think* this change gets that right (based on code reading, not on trying it), but a unit test where one of those matches and the other doesn't would make me feel better.'}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2013-08-15 09:59:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-15 10:56:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Works for me

commit_message:
move if-* header checks to swob

Move the checks for if-* headers out of obj server GET and into swob.

In the immediate term, this will let object HEAD requests respond correctly,
which they currently don't.

In the future, this should let any requests that set an etag or last-modified
header respond correctly to these requests without re-implementing logic.

Change-Id: If7e7858c2cdecc4a35bdb5ad377de6e1e838e588

I believe our setup.py does a bit more than what is listed there because we use pbr, but that should give you the general idea."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-08-16 18:44:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

A quote from the referred document of the expected usage: 'python setup.py install'.

This usage does not requires an executable python file."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-08-16 18:58:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Sure, it's not required, but I have yet to hear a good reason why it shouldn't be there ("some of the other projects are 644" is not a good reason IMHO).

Having the execute bit set allows it to be called as either "python setup.py" or "./setup.py" as the user prefers.  Dropping the execute bit forces the former usage, and gains us...what?

I don't honestly care that much one way or another, but this seems like an arbitrary change that is, if anything, a step backward in functionality.'}, {'account_id': 6763, 'date': '2013-08-17 12:40:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

IMOH, every solution is ok...'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-08-19 09:18:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

@Ben: thanks for the heads up, for some reason my mind refused to look at it as the setuptools script file. I regret my previous suggestion to document this in the README file :(

As afazekas pointed out, the documentation suggests setup.py should not be used as an executable file. In addition to that and as a (personal) general rule, I prefer not to set +x on file unless necessary so I'm still of the idea that this would be good to merge.

@lawrence: I'm still downvoting as I think you should remove the shebang too."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-08-19 14:17:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

You can't remove the shebang from this file.  It's managed by https://github.com/openstack/requirements/blob/master/update.py and if it doesn't match Jenkins will fail.

Honestly, I've spent way too much time on this and I've made my position abundantly clear, so at this point I think I'll just bow out and let the Tempest cores decide what to do with it."}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-08-19 14:50:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Fixes files with wrong bitmode

setup.py have bitmode 755, Changed to 644,
do not remove shebang because of openstack requirements.

Change-Id: I92e140b17514966210c9d816fafaa51a54b64c69

commit_message:
Add support for retrieving group keys

Group keys are keys used by all the hosts listening to a specific
topic. The unqualified topic name is the group name.
Example: conductor, scheduler, ...

Change-Id: Ia5bcdd140cef16e07d4d8ab4030d1ac5cb59212c

'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-08-07 15:35:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

So this seems to work pretty well, but I have a couple of suggestions/concerns.

1. Have you considered the setting of public NOT be on create?  I'm thinking this might be better as a separate API call that allows the original owner or an admin to set a volume as public=True|False after creation. In other words also make a volume no longer public

2. I'm not sure about how you're dealing with the detach and delete here.  It *looks* like you allow any tenant to detach/delete a public volume, that seems like a bad idea.  Seems we should have a public volume be up for grabs, but when a tenant attaches it then it's only allowed to be detached by the user that attached it, or by the admin in the project that it was created.

3. Delete IMO also should only be allowed by the users I called out for the attach.

Finally, we're going to have some merge issues particularly between this and the task-flow change but we'll have to address that after something lands."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-15 06:03:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Abandoned

commit_message:
added service types heat and heat-cfn

This adds the service types for heat to the help text
of service-create. So the types are orchestration
and cloudformation.

Fixes: bug 1211292
Change-Id: I089e6faf183734e6bfdb2dffd5588952a167766c

commit_message:
Raise exceptions instead of calling sys.exit in neutron server

When incorrect configuration is provided to neutron plugin, raise
exceptions with explanation rather silently exit the process.

fixes bug 1209119

Change-Id: Ia670bbb59e9888a51886ced43c31d0285ddbebe9

When create a new network, there is no need to schedule it. When
create a new port, the schedule_network will be called in

commit_message:
Remove schedule_network() call from nicira plugin

When create a new network, there is no need to schedule it. When
create a new port, the schedule_network will be called in
neutron.api.rpc.agentnotifiers.dhcp_rpc_agent_api. The current
behaviour of nicira plugin will cause 'Fail scheduling network'
waring.

Closes-Bug: #1212555

Change-Id: Idfead3138d01357b0ccf074e178b57b23021aba9

commit_message:
Add features to task.Task

Old Task class renamed to BaseTask, and new Task class deriving from it
added in place of it. This new class adds following features:
- if no name is passed to task, name is autogenerated from task type
- all __call__ argument names (except 'context') are added to task
  requirements.

Change-Id: Ied69857932088b6e25d4817d2a8afeddccad36d8

commit_message:
Add get_required_callable_args utility function

Move code that gets callable args from functor task to utils.py and
enhance it to support more use cases.

We do not rely on naming conventions for 'self' and 'cls' parameters any
more; we look at the collable if it is bound method instead.

Change-Id: Ie1a9a7cc727b5fbc2780aba28b1d0253e5bc0ea4

In general it looks pretty good to me. Some suggestion in API extension about request validation.  

On the side note, since the Nova part uses 'swap_volume()' to swap old volume with new one.  Your changes in Nova adds calling to Cinder's migrate_completion.  I don't know the exact use cases when swap_volume() was added in the first place, but I doubt your change there may break those use case (i.e. will cause old volume be deleted which might not be expected result for some users)."}, {'account_id': 7689, 'date': '2013-08-24 17:21:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

Avishay, I tested the changes for this patch set and the other associated ones for volume migration and things worked as expected.  

I tested unattached volumes with and without volume types defined, and in both cases the volume was correctly migrated to backend, and defined metadata was  preserved.  I will try migrating attached volumes next week.

Two observations:
1.  when migrating volumes there is a period of time with both old and new volumes are listed in the output of "cinder list" command, both with status of "available".  You can see the migration status if you "cinder show" the two volumes, but it would be more clear if volume status was set to migration-tgt and migration-src or similar while the migration is in progress.

2.  when you attempt to migrate a volume with volume-type to a backend for a different volume-type, the command fails, and is logged as a failure in scheduler.log, but it would be better to provide feedback of the failure at the command line.

Note:  The testing was done using gpfs driver and uncommitted changes to brick/initiator/connector.py to support local connections.'}, {'account_id': 4355, 'date': '2013-08-25 08:00:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17: (2 inline comments)

Zhiteng: I fixed the inline issues - thanks! This doesn't break calling swap_volume() directly from Nova.  In the migrate_volume_completion API, I check if migration_status is not set for either the source or the destination volume.  If so, then this is a case where swap_volume() was originated from Nova, and therefore we return new_volume['id'].  This is consistent with Nova's previous behavior, where it used the new volume in place of the old volume."}, {'account_id': 4355, 'date': '2013-08-25 08:06:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

Bill: Thanks for testing!

1. With regard to what is shown in 'status'; only the admin should be able to see the new volume that was created.  The non-admin user should not see any difference - no additional volume, no change in status, and should never see migration_status.  The only way a user could know there was a migration going on is if a command failed due to migration in progress - nothing to do about that right now (in the future we could implement an abort method).

2. Unfortunately only the API level can return error codes that are shown on the command line.  The scheduler checks to make sure that the destination back-end can accept the volume, which includes a volume type check.  If this fails, the migration is aborted.  The admin will have to poll occasionally to see when migration_status become None, and when it does, check to see if the host changed. "}, {'created': '2013-08-20 13:42:58.000000000', 'message': "Migration for attached volumes

Enable migration for attached volumes by calling Nova to have the
hypervisor copy the data (Nova's swap_volume feature). A new API
function is added for Nova to call once it is done copying to finish
the Cinder side of the migration.

The overall 'generic' migration flow (i.e., not performed by a driver)
is as follows:
1. Creates a new volume
2a. If the source volume's state is 'available', attach both volumes
    and run 'dd' to copy, then detach both. When finished, call the
    migrate_volume_completion function.
2b. If the source volume's state is 'in-use', call Nova to perform the
    copy. Nova will attach the new volume, copy the data from the
    original volume to the new one, and detach the original volume.
    When the copy completes, Nova will call Cinder's new
    migrate_volume_completion function.
3. The migrate_volume_completion function deletes the original volume,
   and calls the database API's finish_volume_migration function. This
   copies all of the new volume's information to the original, and
   deletes the new volume's row, and thus we can keep using the
   original volume_id (the user sees no change).

We also don't change the original volume's status, and instead add a
migration_status column which only selected users can see (e.g., admin).
The migration status is None when no migration is in progress, whether
it succeeded or failed. The admin should check the volume's current
host to determine success or failure. This is meant to simplify
operations. The user will only be aware of a migration if they try to
change the volume's state during the course of a migration.

As mentioned, we change the volume while keeping the original volume
ID. Because a volume's name depends on its ID, the new volume will have
a different name than the original. This is the purpose of the name_id
field in the database - the name is now based on name_id. So although
we keep the original volume's ID, we use the new volume's ID as the
name_id. Thus we can remove the rename_volume function - it is no
longer necessary because the name_id field in the database already
allows for the volume's name on the backend to not rely on its ID.
The user than can see the migration_status can also see the
name_id, in case they need to find it on the backend.

There were a few other places throughout the code that relied on
constructing a volume's name from its ID, and those were fixed.

DocImpact

Implements: bp online-volume-migration

Change-Id: I8daaee174e426fbd450fa75f04f9c8e6fa09f01a

"}, {'created': '2013-08-21 05:05:57.000000000', 'message': "Migration for attached volumes

Enable migration for attached volumes by calling Nova to have the
hypervisor copy the data (Nova's swap_volume feature). A new API
function is added for Nova to call once it is done copying to finish
the Cinder side of the migration.

The overall 'generic' migration flow (i.e., not performed by a driver)
is as follows:
1. Creates a new volume
2a. If the source volume's state is 'available', attach both volumes
    and run 'dd' to copy, then detach both. When finished, call the
    migrate_volume_completion function.
2b. If the source volume's state is 'in-use', call Nova to perform the
    copy. Nova will attach the new volume, copy the data from the
    original volume to the new one, and detach the original volume.
    When the copy completes, Nova will call Cinder's new
    migrate_volume_completion function.
3. The migrate_volume_completion function deletes the original volume,
   and calls the database API's finish_volume_migration function. This
   copies all of the new volume's information to the original, and
   deletes the new volume's row, and thus we can keep using the
   original volume_id (the user sees no change).

We also don't change the original volume's status, and instead add a
migration_status column which only selected users can see (e.g., admin).
The migration status is None when no migration is in progress, whether
it succeeded or failed. The admin should check the volume's current
host to determine success or failure. This is meant to simplify
operations. The user will only be aware of a migration if they try to
change the volume's state during the course of a migration.

As mentioned, we change the volume while keeping the original volume
ID. Because a volume's name depends on its ID, the new volume will have
a different name than the original. This is the purpose of the name_id
field in the database - the name is now based on name_id. So although
we keep the original volume's ID, we use the new volume's ID as the
name_id. Thus we can remove the rename_volume function - it is no
longer necessary because the name_id field in the database already
allows for the volume's name on the backend to not rely on its ID.
The user than can see the migration_status can also see the
name_id, in case they need to find it on the backend.

There were a few other places throughout the code that relied on
constructing a volume's name from its ID, and those were fixed.

DocImpact

Implements: bp online-volume-migration

Change-Id: I8daaee174e426fbd450fa75f04f9c8e6fa09f01a

commit_message:
Migration for attached volumes

Enable migration for attached volumes by calling Nova to have the
hypervisor copy the data (Nova's swap_volume feature). A new API
function is added for Nova to call once it is done copying to finish
the Cinder side of the migration.

The overall 'generic' migration flow (i.e., not performed by a driver)
is as follows:
1. Creates a new volume
2a. If the source volume's state is 'available', attach both volumes
    and run 'dd' to copy, then detach both. When finished, call the
    migrate_volume_completion function.
2b. If the source volume's state is 'in-use', call Nova to perform the
    copy. Nova will attach the new volume, copy the data from the
    original volume to the new one, and detach the original volume.
    When the copy completes, Nova will call Cinder's new
    migrate_volume_completion function.
3. The migrate_volume_completion function deletes the original volume,
   and calls the database API's finish_volume_migration function. This
   copies all of the new volume's information to the original, and
   deletes the new volume's row, and thus we can keep using the
   original volume_id (the user sees no change).

We also don't change the original volume's status, and instead add a
migration_status column which only selected users can see (e.g., admin).
The migration status is None when no migration is in progress, whether
it succeeded or failed. The admin should check the volume's current
host to determine success or failure. This is meant to simplify
operations. The user will only be aware of a migration if they try to
change the volume's state during the course of a migration.

As mentioned, we change the volume while keeping the original volume
ID. Because a volume's name depends on its ID, the new volume will have
a different name than the original. This is the purpose of the name_id
field in the database - the name is now based on name_id. So although
we keep the original volume's ID, we use the new volume's ID as the
name_id. Thus we can remove the rename_volume function - it is no
longer necessary because the name_id field in the database already
allows for the volume's name on the backend to not rely on its ID.
The user than can see the migration_status can also see the
name_id, in case they need to find it on the backend.

There were a few other places throughout the code that relied on
constructing a volume's name from its ID, and those were fixed.

DocImpact

Implements: bp online-volume-migration

Change-Id: I8daaee174e426fbd450fa75f04f9c8e6fa09f01a

Enumerated options should have the same format for all enumerated options.

This commit moves all options to the {option1,option2} format.

fixes bug: #1155171

Change-Id: I8e0ecf3896c76021cb027cbbbb3b5564a04aacec
'}]
commit_message:
Fix glanceclient usage inconsistences for options

Enumerated options should have the same format for all enumerated options.

This commit moves all options to the {option1,option2} format.

fixes bug: #1155171

Change-Id: I8e0ecf3896c76021cb027cbbbb3b5564a04aacec

commit_message:
Link Service.compute_node with ComputeNode object

This is the third in a three-step dance to implement a Service
object, a ComputeNode object, and finish the relationship with
the circular reference from Service to ComputeNode. It adds
Service.compute_node, a nested object relationship that is either
lazy-loaded on access, or pre-loaded if a database query
includes it. This should exactly match the behavior of the
SQLAlchemy objects that we have now.

Note that this requires a new DB API method to look up a
ComputeNode object from its service_id. This was previously
provided by the SQLAlchemy relationship between the two objects.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: If62d443e34a3c8ce9bc83008fc69821494686bc7

commit_message:
Use qemu as virt engine when kvm not available

By default, kvm is always use as the hypervisor when booting the seed
image, regardless it is available of not.

Test if kvm is loaded. If not, change default hypervisor to qemu.

Change-Id: Ia68d2c0d37e68abc1932376a3757ffe94a9a6662

commit_message:
Refactor path splitting and validation.

The account, container, and object servers all do the same thing at
the top of GET/PUT/etc.: they split the path, validate that the first
two components are a good (device, partition) pair, and return a 400
if they're not. The object server already had a module-local helper
function for this, but the account and container servers just had
duplicate boilerplate code. Now it's all in one common helper.

Change-Id: I9a20d37fc9e1a68b10149a7aa78cb9691fc04ea9

So, Morgan put me onto this and so may have a better answer but to my understanding:

This happens when testing grizzly.
Grizzly will depend on/can work with a version of keystoneclient less than current and dependencies will be filled for this version of the client.
Our test code for checking old versions of keystoneclient also tests against the current master branch which has this new dependency, but these are git checkouts and not 'installed'.
So old server code and environment setup with new client code = this bug with missing dep.

So this is a ridiculous situation and we need to cleanup how we test old versions of keystoneclient, this is just a fix to keep the gate from failing.

I'll rewrite the message to try to make it clearer."}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-08-26 00:07:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-26 00:47:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Add netaddr to test requirements

Because of the way we do old keystoneclient tests we can end up with the
situation where an old keystone uses a newer keystoneclient without
doing an install and so misses out on the newer dependencies.

This patch is not a solution to the underlying problem, but should
prevent current gate failings.

Fixes: bug 1212939
Change-Id: I25eca24c6820611a5937a1f709ba42620b70b304

commit_message:
Fix v3 extensions inherit from wrong controller

Extensions keypairs and config_drive's controller should
inherit from nova.api.openstack.wsgi.Controller. Inherit
from wrong controller may cause strange errors.

Partially implements bp v3-api-extension-versioning

Change-Id: I5e2a588960bf6b1c0afafb89ecaab255dbd2a1f4

To support PCI devices passthrough, we keep all assignable PCI devices
information on database.

Two major object is created, one is PCI device object which present
one specific pci devices on a host. HostPciDevice presents a list for
all devices in one specific host.

The resource tracker in compote node will manage the HostPciDevice object
and save them if something changed. There will be no method to save a single
PCI devices.

This is a draft to get feedback from others.

commit_message:
Add PCI device object support

To support PCI passthrough, we keep all assignable PCI device information
in the database. Two objects are provided to access the pci devices.
PciDevice represents one specific PCI device on a compute node, and
PciDeviceList represents a list of pci devices.

A resource tracker on each compute node manages the PciDevice objects,
keeping track of their status and instance allocation.

bp:pci-passthrough-base

Change-Id: Ib69cc448277dc197331556c622fb77937009f276
Signed-off-by: Yongli He <yongli.he@intel.com>
Signed-off-by: Yunhong Jiang <yunhong.jiang@intel.com>

Hi, Boris

i notice from this commit, the node and the host had different meaning.

commit 885cf0949ab2e116da39143c2f6469362367ec7d
Author: Mikyung Kang <mkkang@isi.edu>
Date:   Sat Nov 10 10:20:45 2012 +0900

    Updated scheduler and compute for multiple capabilities.
    
    Part 1 of 6: blueprint general-bare-metal-provisioning-framework.
    
    This patch includes updates on scheduler and compute codes for
    multiple capabilities. This feature is needed in bare-metal
    provisioning which is implemented in later patches --- a bare-metal
    nova-compute manages multiple bare-metal nodes where instances are
    provisioned. Nova DB's compute_nodes entry needs to be created for
    each bare-metal node, and a scheduler can choose an appropriate
    bare-metal node to provision an instance.
    
    With this patch, one service entry with multiple compute_node entries
    can be registered by nova-compute. Distinct 'node name' is given for
    each node and is stored at compute_node['hypervisor_hostname'].
    And we added a new column "node" to "instances" table in Nova DB to
    associate instances with compute_node. FilterScheduler puts <nodename>
    to the column when it provisions the instance. And nova-computes
    respect <nodename> when run/stop instances and when calculate
    resources.
    
    Also, 'capability is extended from a dictionary to a list of
    dictionaries to describe the multiple capabilities of the multiple
    nodes.'}, {'account_id': 7543, 'date': '2013-08-19 06:45:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 14.'}, {'account_id': 7543, 'date': '2013-08-19 06:48:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: (4 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 7543, 'date': '2013-08-19 07:20:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 15.'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2013-08-19 07:25:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Yongli, 

Thanks for addressing align things, the last thing is host and node column. 

Actually that text is addressed to "bare metal" not typical virtualization (e.g. libvirt) in case of bare metal one compute node manage a lot of physical servers. As we are managing physical servers and use bare metal we won't use pci passthrough at all. 

In case of typical virtualization (libvirt), each physical server has only one compute_node record, and this compute_node record store host name in 'hypervisor_name'  column which is equivalent to real host name and  must be unique for each physical server.

So I think in our case it is enough to use just "host" to store host name of physical server.'}, {'account_id': 7543, 'date': '2013-08-19 08:15:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

thank your explain, but i kind of worry some hyper-visor driver will support multi node and might had something with pci.

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/multiple-clusters-managed-by-one-service

and the multi node support is kind of general feature, even though libvirt does not support it yet, but this is not too over design, what do you think of this?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-19 08:44:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: Works for me

commit_message:
Pci Device DB support

Add a new table to store information about available PCI devices on
compute nodes and related APIs to fetch and update these devices
information.

Add a summary PCI device column to compute node table so that
scheduler doesn't need joinload to get the PCI information.

Co-authored-by: Boris Pavlovic <boris@pavlovic.me>

bp:pci-passthrough-base

Change-Id:I9ca8fe689a7ef1c4f22dec8640a018c0adff773c

commit_message:
Make nbd reservation thread-safe

Avoid the situation where two local threads choose the same nbd number
for injecting files into the instance. If this happened quickly enough
nova was left with one qemu-nbd hanging and blocking the device forever.

Fixes bug 1207422

Change-Id: I18864b19ebd30669534e45ca7a50e12f61207302

commit_message:
chore: remove queue_id cruft in mongo driver

We store queue name in message schema; there is no need to query for
queue ID.  Some `queue_id` param are left in comments, this patch
replaces them with `queue_name`.

Change-Id: I260007f0d6091b46755f374d9e237c0a7ab372ef

commit_message:
Add _safe_for_slave decorator to sqlalchemy db api

Queries can be sent to a slave db handle conditional upon your context
being tolerant of slightly older data. This decorator allows us to
specify from the sqlalchemy api which queries would be safe to run on
a slave given a safe context.

Implements: blueprint db-slave-handle
Change-Id: I18984c6db97b63037cb2941976e0ae67d2781ba7

'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-08-01 12:05:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Not sure we need this in the context.

In your example, it seems having an optional DB param something like "ensure_fresh=False" that dictates which type of session to open seems a bit better.

I don't like the idea of updating the context, then calling something else with an existing context that still has save_for_slave marked on it.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-08-01 17:56:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

@John: I felt the same way at first.  Here's an example of how it would be used:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38872/

To do this same thing, it would change a lot more code to get it from the compute manager, nova instance object, nova conductor rpc api, nova conductor api, db api, sqlalchemy api.  I'm afraid we'd end up with an exposion of this parameter through much of nova.

The example of setting it in a periodic task is a pretty good one.  It points out that the primary use case for this really is a context-aware thing.  When we're in a periodic task, reading from a slave is OK.

So, I think I've come around to be OK with the context approach.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-08-01 19:33:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I'm slightly conflicted here as well. It seems like packing more stuff into the context is always something we should look at with a critical eye. However, this seems roughly akin to 'read_deleted'. However, read_deleted is a point of confusion all over, I think, that could be much clearer if it were a property on the actual db call instead of something that was set much earlier.

I guess it seems like the way objects cuts out a lot of the need for modifying a ton of different "middle methods" such as conductor and compute manager, it would be more realistic to have a "lazy" parameter to those query methods without making lots of changes everywhere. That said, maybe this is not worth arguing over, I'm just not sure...'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-08-01 19:37:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: No score

I'm definitely conflicted, too.  Maybe it's not subject to the level of explosion as I was initially afraid of.  Maybe someone needs to hack up an attempt at the alternative for the use case in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38872/ ?"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-08-01 19:43:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

The way objects' remoting works, the only layers that need to change to add a new argument or query method are the one that talks to the db and the one at the actual query site. All the goo in the middle remains unmolested, which is a departure from how we normally have to make that sort of change.

So, I'm just saying, I think it's more doable now than before. That is orthogonal to whether this belongs in context from a philosophical point of view, I think."}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2013-08-01 20:07:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I think I said it in one of the first patch sets... but I'll say again:  I'm definitely not a huge fan of using the context in this way.  I think the other alternative, as John mentioned, is adding some kwargs to DB calls.  Not sure what I think about that, either. ;)  Would need to think some more, but I think I'd actually lean towards the latter (kwargs)."}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2013-08-01 21:07:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I feel late to the party, but I also lean towards not having this in the context.  But that's mainly because the context is pegged as representing a user making a request.

I think using the context is a very clean solution, but it expands the scope a little bit.  If we want to go this way lets not treat it as something sneaky, but start to think of the context a little differently."}, {'account_id': 4912, 'date': '2013-08-08 16:51:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Please check out https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38872/ for a different approach that doesn't mess with context. Thx to everyone for the feedback btw."}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-08-10 00:01:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I not only think this is the most practical approach (even before seeing https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38872/7), I also think it is the right approach, and imo it doesn't necessarily pose a conflict with the current notion of what the context is/does.

So +1 for the approach.

I do think the 'can_lag' name can be a bit confusing at first, and may force ppl to stop for 2 seconds and read the docs. How about something more explicit, yet high-level enough, like "use_replica" or something involving the fact that the request may access the replica db, and doesn't need the master db.

I would -1 for the property name, but +1 since the current debate is whether to even use this approach or not.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-08-11 16:03:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: No score

Interesting discussion. I like the idea of keeping the context out of this. I have just been burnt by software that where context grew to a monster, I feel we should keep this only containing info about the user request, if possible.

kwargs are messy, but that seems a little nicer that accidentally fetching a cached version of something because context is shared between several unrelated db calls.

Dan/Chris, how does the alternative review look re the object system?'}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2013-08-23 18:02:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I've been pondering for some time whether the context should actually be split into two partsone for user-specific context information (call it "authorization context"?), and one for application-specific context information (read_deleted, maybe this can_lag attribute or an alternative).  If we did that, I would expect the authorization context would end up being a member of the application context, but it would split the responsibilities quite well.  But, that's a side discussion

On the issue of this specific patch, I waffle; it seems like the objects approach would be cleaner, given what Dan says about the goo in the middle, but I don't know how long it would take to finish objects or how it would interact with this can_lag attribute.  I will agree with the note on the name of the attribute, however; maybe a name like "slave_ok" would be better?'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-08-23 18:12:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Kevin/John,

He's already cooked up the do-it-with-objects approach. Much cleaner and more explicit, IMHO. Check his other reviews, as I expect it's still pending."}, {'account_id': 4912, 'date': '2013-08-27 22:35:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Abandoned

Thx all for the feedback, the objects approach wins in my mind. It is much more explicit and therefore much safer and easily maintainable. Therefore, I'm going to abandon this review. If we ever do get the two context thing that Kevin is talking about then this might belong in there. But I don't think it's great to expand the scope of context without a compelling reason, and this doesn't seem to be one when it fits in objects land so well."}]

commit_message:
Add can_lag flag to Context class

The can_lag flag should indicate that the context is able to
do its job even when data it gets from the db is possibly up to
a few seconds older.

Implements: blueprint db-slave-handle
Change-Id: I54d8630d006bb5b00c4f59ead20c178caf7eda55

commit_message:
Adds ability to ignore hacking validations with noqa

Add allownoqa decorator that can be applied to any of the hacking
core functions.  This allows a using application to bypass that
particular hacking validation.  The reason this is being introduced
is because I need to bypass H231 and H233, both Python 3.x
validations.  I need to bypass these so we can run pep8 validations
on the nova XenServer plugins.  XenServer usese Python 2.4 in its
environment and therefore the code won't pass those two or future
Python 3.x validations.

It is understood that a patch to hacking won't be held up or reverted
if it breaks anything Python 2.4 related, including breaking of this
patch.

Change-Id: Iea3867b84212ab30bdd168b5dbd43c11a4dc535e

[{'created': '2013-08-27 17:56:29.000000000', 'message': "Refine the returned 'content-encodings' for secret metadata to be like 'content-types'.

When secret metadata is returned, the 'content-types' for a secret are returned as a dict that
has at least a 'default' key. However, the 'content-encodings' are returned as a simple list.
This blueprint is to also return the encodings as a dict, for consistency.

Implements: blueprint api-secret-get-encodings-refine

Change-Id: Iaaa7c13e0a2103d39f5d8425ca08b9aee849417c
"}, {'created': '2013-08-27 21:26:58.000000000', 'message': "Refine the Secret metadata response by *not* returning the 'content-encodings'.

The 'content-encodings' for Secrets define the types of transfer protocols available
to retrieve stored Secret data with. This really should be negotiated between the
client and server at the HTTP level, so there is no need for Barbican to provide
a list of such 'content-encodings' for clients to use. Thus clients will receive a
406 response if they specify an Accept-Encoding not supported by Barbican. The API
documentation will be updated to reflect this point.

Implements: blueprint api-secret-get-encodings-refine

Change-Id: Iaaa7c13e0a2103d39f5d8425ca08b9aee849417c
"}]
commit_message:
Refine the Secret metadata response by *not* returning the 'content-encodings'.

The 'content-encodings' for Secrets define the types of transfer protocols available
to retrieve stored Secret data with. This really should be negotiated between the
client and server at the HTTP level, so there is no need for Barbican to provide
a list of such 'content-encodings' for clients to use. Thus clients will receive a
406 response if they specify an Accept-Encoding not supported by Barbican. The API
documentation will be updated to reflect this point.

Implements: blueprint api-secret-get-encodings-refine

Change-Id: Iaaa7c13e0a2103d39f5d8425ca08b9aee849417c

commit_message:
Update TripleO projects.

TripleO is now entirely in the openstack/ project rather than
stackforge. Also there was a typo preventing our most active project
being counted!

Change-Id: I8e77baf6a066a47c6693d1385ddc8d03c5c315ff

(3 inline comments)

So, in my opinion the goals here are noble, but I think the task object implementation is a bit premature. If we had task flow management of defined task objects, this would make sense to me. However, since we don't, I think that putting everything into a baseless object with a single (argument-less) execute method is just kindof messy and a bit confusing.

I think I'd prefer to just see the stuff in the task module implemented there as a module (instead of wrapped in an object) and called from the manager until we have a reason for the encapsulation.

That said, if I'm the only one that thinks that wrapping it in an object is awkward at this stage, I'll happily keep to myself :D"}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-06-10 17:06:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: (4 inline comments)

When we discussed this on IRC on Friday, I think the best solution I heard was to put the rollback code (currently in the except clause that wraps your call to execute) in a rollback method, so that it becomes:

  try:
    foo.execute()
  except:
    foo.rollback()

That should be super easy, and would at least justify all the rest of the object stuff there, I think.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-06-11 08:27:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-05-29 12:06:31.000000000', 'message': 'Move live-migration control flow from scheduler to conductor

This builds on the previous two patches that moved code to
the conductor and adding the conductor into the control path.

We take care to ensure this works with a local conductor, but
running the code in a greenlet thread, but this will work best
when conductor is run as a standalone service.

The next steps are to move more logic from the compute manager
into the conductor, then to start supporting dealing with
tasks that get stopped half way though execution.

part of blueprint live-migration-to-conductor

Change-Id: I4120156db1499dfd3ed22095e528787eb73d33a6
'}, {'created': '2013-05-29 17:24:02.000000000', 'message': 'Move live-migration control flow from scheduler to conductor

This builds on the previous two patches that moved code to
the conductor and adding the conductor into the control path.

We take care to ensure this works with a local conductor, but
running the code in a greenlet thread, but this will work best
when conductor is run as a standalone service.

The next steps are to move more logic from the compute manager
into the conductor, then to start supporting dealing with
tasks that get stopped half way though execution.

commit_message:
Move live-migration control flow from scheduler to conductor

This builds on previous patches that moved code to
the conductor and adding the conductor into the control path.

We take care to ensure this works with a local conductor, but
running the code in a greenlet thread, but this will work best
when conductor is run as a standalone service.

The next steps are to move more logic from the compute manager
into the conductor, then to start supporting dealing with
tasks that get stopped half way though execution.

Part of blueprint live-migration-to-conductor
Change-Id: I4120156db1499dfd3ed22095e528787eb73d33a6

commit_message:
Updated End User guide to include Uploading Images using Dashboard

Included a procedure in the end user guide to upload an image using the dashboard, as an end user. Includes a sentence saying these
actions can be performed only if the cloud operator/admin have granted
the end user permissions to do so.

Change-Id: If37f2de9f21cbfcffa1e4e0bc04c7dadcc88eb91

commit_message:
Update cinder.conf.sample

cinder.conf.sample is quite out of date with the
current state of the tree.  Updating it here should
make it easier to merge upcoming patchsets.

This also means we can -1 patchsets that change cfg
opts without running the conf update script, but not
make people wade through options that aren't related
to their patch.

Change-Id: I0c50ff2e3666ef8ca4e61bcf80dc03ff6400dfc4

commit_message:
Check examples when running tests

Add testcase that executes all examples from taskflow/examples
directory. For examples with somewhat deterministic output the output
is also checked.

This commit also fixes couple of examples broken by recent decorators
refactoring.

Change-Id: I3e65eabde43e1dd26b442d8f7dd3f062bf80703d

commit_message:
Require uuid + move functor_task to task.py

Require details have a uuid of an originating
runner, remove tasks having there own uuid since
only when a task is added to a flow does it obtain
a uuid.

Move functor_task to task.py since it is task releated
and seems better connected in task.py instead of as its
own module.

Change-Id: I8c441e184afcdd697d077f166f2e550fcafcd385

commit_message:
add TEMPEST_LARGE_OPS_NUMBER to option

The tempest scenario.large_ops test tries to catch any performance issues
when running large numbers of operations at once, in this case launching
instances.

Set to 0 by default, to maintain the current default, but add this as an
option so this can be set via devstacks localrc.

Part of regression test for bug 1199433

Change-Id: I459717b849f9b6d180a7956c0ff470cefe7c1ff6

[{'created': '2013-08-26 12:25:51.000000000', 'message': "Stylistic improvement of compute.api.API.update()

The previous implementation of compute.api.API.update() method included
a line of code where the '_' identifier was used to hold a throw-away
variable. Such a usage of underscores is generally not a good style and,
more importantly, it can possibly lead to a name conflict with the '_'
function imported as 'from nova.openstack.common.gettextutils import _'
in several modules of the system.

The present patch fixes the above, as well as some indent issues in the code.

Change-Id: I7a904109f4809fd677ded06b7eea3205c38a369b
"}]
commit_message:
Stylistic improvement of compute.api.API.update()

The previous implementation of compute.api.API.update() method included
a line of code where the '_' identifier was used to hold a throw-away
variable. Such a usage of underscores is generally not a good style and,
more importantly, it can possibly lead to a name conflict with the '_'
function imported as 'from nova.openstack.common.gettextutils import _'
in several modules of the system.

The present patch fixes the above, as well as some indent issues in the code.

Change-Id: I7a904109f4809fd677ded06b7eea3205c38a369b

commit_message:
VMware: provide a coherent message to user when viewing console log

The vCenter and ESX returns a PNG format. Currently there is no way
to display a text based format. This at least provides the user with
a message that is informative.

Fixes bug: 1199754

Change-Id: I382219ca89a1574ca233b0f25a89af63af71a22f

commit_message:
Rename OS::Metering::Alarm to OS::Ceilometer::Alarm

The other resources are named by project so this is to
try and be more consistent.

There is a mapping to allow the original name to work.

Change-Id: If60cc577a5a770bdaada70c7eae1ae3fc1776056

commit_message:
Catch a NotFound exception in signal_responder delete

If the alarm does not get created (error condition) and
the url does not get created (no one referenced it) then
the delete will fail with a NotFound.

Change-Id: I431ebef9b9341548176d977e336558df9f5deb6c

subject: Add support for setting Neutron DHCP agent options.
messages:
[{'account_id': 105, 'date': '2013-08-22 03:38:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Rather than continuing to add individual config parameters into devstack for Neutron, I'd prefer we do what we did for the Neutron server and agents by adding something like this in the DHCP config file setup function here:

# Define extra "DEFAULT" configuration options when q-dhcp is configured by
# defining the array ``Q_DHCP_EXTRA_DEFAULT_OPTS``.
# For Example: ``Q_DHCP_EXTRA_DEFAULT_OPTS=(foo=true bar=2)``
for I in "${Q_DHCP_EXTRA_DEFAULT_OPTS[@]}"; do
    # Replace the first '=' with ' ' for iniset syntax
    iniset $Q_DHCP_CONF_FILE DEFAULT ${I/=/ }
done

And then in your localrc you would set this up as:

Q_DHCP_EXTRA_DEFAULT_OPTS=(enable_multihost=True)

In this way, when the next DHCP option is needed, we no longer need a devstack patch.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2013-08-22 15:36:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Nachi, I should note that I gave the review based on advice I received from sdague on a review where I was trying to expose VXLAN vs. GRE configuration into devstack [1]. He was pretty clear he wanted new devstack patches to expose the ability to configure options set in localrc rather than expose each individual option in devstack itself. Just wanted to clarify here.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/30315/'}, {'account_id': 2031, 'date': '2013-08-22 17:05:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add support for setting Neutron DHCP agent options.

This patch adds support for setting arbitrary Neutron DHCP agent options.
An example of using it would be to add this to your localrc:

    Q_DHCP_EXTRA_DEFAULT_OPTS=(enable_multihost=True)

Change-Id: I56d267eafa06c52c3867e3396483f5fde3ee5570

commit_message:
VMware: update cinder support for VMware configuration settings

The review https://review.openstack.org/#/c/41600 was update to
have a 'vmware' prefix for all of the VMware cinder settings. These
were previously in a 'vmware' section and now they are in the
'DEFAULT' section.

commit_message:
Add support for resource pool in VMware Drivers

Currently, VMware drivers boot instances in the root resource
pool of a compute resource (host or cluster). This patch allows
admins to specify a resource pool inside the compute resource.

Fixes: bug #1105032

Change-Id: I8ecf65dd9dfbf3a22ddcfb8f6822fea8fc6a77f1

commit_message:
Add X-Region-Name parameter in HTTP request

In order to specify region_name, we let client send
the OS_REGION_NAME in header file

Fixes bug 1213291

Change-Id: Ie44f700ca7e412c2504b6b8faac3fd65d4fd744b

commit_message:
EC2-API: Fix ambiguous ipAddress/dnsName issue

Currently, the public ipAddress and dnsName take in either the
fixed or floating IP address as a value. The current fix ensures
that the public dnsName and the public ipAddress both get only
the floating ip address. A look into Amazon's EC2 API Reference
tells us that if there is no public IP associated with an instance,
an empty value is returned for <dnsName> and the key <ipAddress>
itself is never returned. This was tested with euca2ools.
Also, the key <publicDnsName> has been removed since it is
the same as <dnsName>

Fixes: bug #1096468

Change-Id: I3b3e3b3f815df41d1976444d33604363e64a7709

commit_message:
Add linuxbridge plugin recipe

* add linuxbridge plugin package attr
* add recipe install linuxbridge-plugin and agent package
* add chef spec example to test
* prevent to create external bridge with openvswitch in l3-agent recipe

Change-Id: Ibea546cea1c3742274c5e9d30bd15bf33ed91edf

commit_message:
Add some flexibility for upload server details

Created new env variable with the format of
TOCI_RESULTS_DST=user@server:path

This is required for jenkins jobs that will upload to a different path
on the results server.

Change-Id: If7cc9ff50852d956e88faa1f090a8a1967546391

commit_message:
Show Neutron floating IPs quotas on Overview

Display the correct limits and usage when Neutron is in use and the
quotas extension is enabled. If Neutron is enabled but the quotas
extensions is not supported, assume the floating IPs quota is
unlimited (a floating IP quota is expected to exist in other places,
e.g. Security and Access panel)

Because quotas may not be configured or enabled even if the extension
is available, add an 'enable_quotas' setting.

Partial-Bug: #1109140

Change-Id: Id6345f4700f0ff45be8ce8acb69cca0d4e05e14a

commit_message:
Add VPCZoneIdentifier attribute for autoscaling

For now, only one subnet can be specified in the launch configuration because
Neutron doesn't have the ability to map subnets with availability zones.
See bug #1096017 for details.

Change-Id: I46ef4d17b2109c97664f7606c97b16071553ebcd
Fixes: bug #1196494
