commit_message:
Removes V3 API images and image_metadata extensions

Removes V3 API images and image_metadata extensions as the
same functionality can be accessed directly through glance. Also
removes the associated testcases. There is a discussion about
the decision here:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-August/012958.html

Fixes the image bookmark links in server information requests
so they point to glance

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Id32be0c0794b0f4dd220a928345ddf0133e9ffca

commit_message:
Extlinux fallback

If GRUB2 is not available in the system a fallback to install Extlinux
will happen. This patch also allows you to enforce the use of Extlinux
exporting the DIB_EXTLINUX variable.

Change-Id: I88fa792a0bd19cacca167134f2054b11c807a451

commit_message:
pin keyring to < 2.0

keyring 2.0.0 (released aug 18, 2013) contains a regression on ubuntu
regarding GnomeKeyring, see comment #5 by Pavel on:

    https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/python-keyring/+bug/1197988

Change-Id: I3320da4f13cded498d6622525d56c31ae9936e0f
Closes-Bug: 1193164

subject: Rename 51-grub to 51-bootloader
messages:
[{'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2013-08-22 14:15:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2013-08-22 16:44:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Wondering if we should use extlinux instead of grub by default. One problem I can see with this are kernel upgrades where the post scritps would triger a grub-update but apart from that extlinux is an absolutely a great thing!'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-08-22 16:50:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hi Lucas, gerrit may be confused, or you may have done this in an odd way, but the rename from 51-grub to 51-bootloader should be tracked as a rename, not an Add/Delete.

Can you please try re-doing it by doing a 'git mv' and then applying the patch to the new file? That usually works for me."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2013-08-23 08:33:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hey Clint, yea I was surprise with this as well, even commented with a guy from my work. I didn't do anything different I simple moved the file to rename it (using normal mv not git mv), then I did my changes and added it. Anywayyy, I'm going to send a new patch."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2013-08-23 08:44:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Ok! I just did it again using "git mv" and all, but the patch came out exactly the same, when I look at the diff it says that 51-grub script was deleted and the 51-bootloader was added. I even got a  "HEAD -> refs/publish/master/extlinux-fallback (no changes made)!" when I tried to git review it.

I did some substantial changes on the script, for e.g all the grub logic is now indented.

Anyway here's the diff: http://paste.fedoraproject.org/34208/'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-08-25 22:32:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Oh, so this is just 'welcome to git, it's terrible'.

What you need to do in a git world is two separate patches: one that moves, one that fixes it up."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-08-25 22:33:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

This needs rebasing due to the other mapping change that just landed. Please split into two at the same time - one that just renames grub->bootloader, then the actual patch.

commit_message:
Rename 51-grub to 51-bootloader

This patch is part of a another big patch that will implement a fallback
to Extlinux in case GRUB2 is not available in the system. The reason why
it's being splitted in two patches is because git is not being able to
recognize the file changes when the rename happens in the same commit.

Change-Id: Ic2027dfa057fd6d62b532203b7ff50c3c739bccb

commit_message:
enable multiple neutron-server worker processes

Fixes bug 1214132.

This patch makes it easy to launch a bunch of neutron-server processes
on a host. Deploying multiple neutron-server workers per host avoids
serialization on database accesses caused by libmysqlclient.so
blocking eventlet's single thread.

This patch makes use of the same multi-process service launching code
used in nova, neutron.openstack.common.service.ProcessLauncher. The
bulk of this patch moves the socket and listen system calls before the
fork call.

Adds workers=N to the [DEFAULT] section of neutron.conf.

Change-Id: I0a46855e905740f76fa49200626e14f3f9bae78d

Consolidation of brick exceptions into a single
brick exception.py file neglected to updated files
that were using it:
    (see change I577d403f02c2fd0d727d2694776008e1e9791453)

The result is the lvm driver was doing an except on lvm.VolumeGroupNotFound
which didn't exist anymore as it's in brick/exception now.

Fixes: bug 1216122

commit_message:
Fix except in lvm.py

Consolidation of brick exceptions into a single
brick exception.py file neglected to updated files
that were using it:
    (see change I577d403f02c2fd0d727d2694776008e1e9791453)

The result is the lvm driver was doing an except on lvm.VolumeGroupNotFound
which didn't exist anymore as it's in brick/exception now.

We still need to clean up exceptions all through here, and this still
isn't handled by service init anyway, but at least with this we are
raising a valid exception.

Change-Id: I588e9ac6548823b291d284f68f6133879bf3dfbf
Fixes: bug 1216122

commit_message:
Don't delete failed instances in InstanceGroup

This gets rid of the code to delete failed instances in
InstanceGroup so that administrators can debug what happened
if any instances fail to start. It also allows the resize operation
to raise an error, so the InstanceGroup should be in a FAILED state
after a failed resize operation.

fixes bug 1214007
fixes bug 1215140

Change-Id: Id508195c847f09dd986e450f35876ff574ff7673

commit_message:
Remove deprecated legacy network info model in Hypervisor drivers

This patch removes legacy network info wihch is unused in any Hypervisor
drivers, clean up related tests and Also removes legacy method from
nova.network.model.

Partly implement blueprint nova-network-legacy

Change-Id: Ia3f11b1a162878817445619575b35187110dafb5

commit_message:
Removes exception instance creation on execute()

For every excption raised in utils.execute(), a new instance is created.
This patch removes this redundant step and directly uses exceptions
defined in Oslo.

Change-Id: I1425d7f1d69a8fde8fde29444fae4d12d045b730

commit_message:
Libvirt: fix KeyError in set_vif_bandwidth_config

The set_vif_bandwidth_config function must be able to get a parameter that has
no 'extra_specs' field and not fail.

This fixes bug 1214363.

Change-Id: I576fb087c7bcda9f6662c4df5b480668b1f23454

Currently, libvirt driver doesn't pass the 'os_type' property to
glance. Thus all snapshots created don't have this property. Other
feature depend on 'os_type'(such as mkfs for ephemeral devices)
doesn't work.

This patch fixes this by passing the 'os_type' attribute to glance

"}]
commit_message:
libvirt: allow passing 'os_type' property to glance

Currently, libvirt driver doesn't pass the 'os_type' property to
glance. Thus all snapshots created don't have this property. Other
feature depend on 'os_type'(such as mkfs for ephemeral devices)
doesn't work.

This patch fixes this by passing the 'os_type' attribute to glance
as image properties. None value in metadata properties would not be
passed to glance, thus this patch has no side effect on situation
when instance has no 'os_type' attribute set.

Bug 1214372

Change-Id: I2bab617f6c1e8866650ca7dc5178b640738c9ae6

commit_message:
Enable no_parent and file_only security

The websockify package was recently upgraded to version 0.5.1, which added two
parameters that provide additional security:
* no_parent - returns 403 response if contents out of the web root are
requested. Required to disable directory traversal.
* file_only - returns 404 response if non-file contents are requested. Required
to disable directory listing.
This version is available in PyPi.

Nova should upgrade it's required version for websockify, and set these
parameters while creating and starting the NovaWebSocketProxy to ensure
better security.

DocImpact
Fixes bug #1195700

Change-Id: I9c4b28eb1b384048f10d365ed204b916afd371bb

commit_message:
Fix migrations index

`deleted` column in `migrations`.`migrations_by_host_nodes_and_status_idx`
index had been dropped after some migration.

This patch fixes this.

bp: db-sync-models-with-migrations

Change-Id: Ifd2e567b5beeeb027a72d5d35d8cb3405a5a1942

commit_message:
Remove backup resources on stack delete

If any resources are cached as backups after a failed stack update +
rollback, ensure they are deleted when the stack itself is deleted.

Change-Id: I1e271cec146681759cc657ba82c205a648339ec1

commit_message:
Add a DB API to swap two resources between stacks

When rolling back a stack update, we will need to swap the current and
previous (backup) resources so that the former moves to the backup stack
while the latter returns to the current stack. This API allows us to effect
the switch using a database transaction (thus avoiding having to create a
*third* stack).

Change-Id: I2b7247e384e3914778179260e198e5ae5c701525

I'm really twofold on this.

First of all, I'd love to see the requirement of node.js moved out here. A big plus is also to remove the bundled less.js 

The main reason, why lesscpy shall introduced here is to alleviate deployments. This is, what I don't get. I'm preferring to use pre-compressed css, js etc. In that way, you don't need less.js, and node.js on any production system.

I'd love to see a broader discussion on this topic, since already the introduction of node.js was a real pain and drew lots of discussion...

Also there is the (slowly) ongoing discussion about websockets which might re-introduce node.js on ANY production system."}, {'account_id': 1816, 'date': '2013-07-30 19:14:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm generally good with this. At the time there hadn't been any pure-python LESS compiler, hence Node. I can understand why Node can be a discouragement to some people despite the ability to use precompiled stylesheets as Matthias said.

I'm good with this change once it properly goes through Jenkins and gets some more documentation."}, {'account_id': 4375, 'date': '2013-07-31 15:16:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-31 16:13:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Drop NodeJS dependency in favor of pure-python lesscpy

While less.js from lesscss.org is still the most standard-compliant (err
defining) LESS implementation, a pure-python one will drasticly simplify
deployments.

Since lesscpy doesn't support {outfile} just write to stdout,
django_compressor will happily take that (See
http://django-compressor.readthedocs.org/en/master/settings/#django.conf.settings.COMPRESS_PRECOMPILERS)

Drop dependency documentation, there are no external (non-Python) tools
left to setup.

Meanwhile, lesscpy(>=0.9j) supports SVG stylesheets.

Change-Id: I89ed102f7be4b554a28b001c9c0d40dab4a51ae6

[{'created': '2013-07-30 08:38:19.000000000', 'message': "Fine-grained policy control about security-group.

Now the policies about security-group are too simple,
which can't enforce actions like 'index/update/delete/create'.

The patch add policy rules about security-groups.
The new polices include:
* index/update/delete/create/show security-groups.
* create/delete security-group rules.

Since create/update/delete/create security groups and rules are
in Neutron, do not port these to nova V3 API.

Implemented bp: enforce-security-policy

Change-Id: I302e482b008e82bf5bae0bd93b036776d2784939

commit_message:
Fine-grained policy control about security-group

Now the policies about security-group are too simple,
which can't enforce actions like 'index/update/delete/create'.

The patch add policy rules about security-groups.
The new polices include:
* index/update/delete/create/show security-groups.
* create/delete security-group rules.

Since create/update/delete/create security groups and rules are
in Neutron, do not port these to nova V3 API.

Implemented bp: enforce-security-policy

DocImpact

Change-Id: I302e482b008e82bf5bae0bd93b036776d2784939

commit_message:
Fix setdefault() for swob's HeaderKeyDict.

You'd think this would just work, given that HeaderKeyDict inherits
from dict and overrides the usual __thingy__ methods, but it
doesn't. It would work if you title-cased the key, but the whole point
of HeaderKeyDict is to do that for you.

Change-Id: If5c22df0690a245d1dd02fa3a52fa135235fe60d

commit_message:
Adds param check logic on v2 api server update method

This patch adds the necessary check logic on v2 server
update method to fix the issue which 200 ok is returned
even the param is missing or invalid.

Partially fixes bug #1213812

Change-Id: I5a3a259e51c204e607902d68586d02392049f7bc

commit_message:
Removing misleading error message

This function (_get_instances_on_driver) was reporting instances are on the
hypervisor and not in the database with no consideration for the filters being
used in the database query. This resulted in error log messages indicating running
instances were not in the database when in fact the query was filtering for deleted
instances.

To avoid misleading error logs of this nature I've removed the logging from the
function. Currently the locations which call this function provide more accurate
logging on the state of the instances that are returned based on the filters they
have called _get_instances_on_driver with.

bug 1183276

Change-Id: I4ee52fe417f73a90cf157bc531b483be93e34275

Anyhow, whatever the cause this fix is insufficient as the very next steps will be to build an undercloud image then an overcloud image.

I suggest the thing to do is to hint the working set size we'll need to dib, and then let dib choose to avoid tmpfs."}, {'account_id': 1726, 'date': '2013-08-27 07:46:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-23 08:46:45.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid using tempfs by default when not enough RAM avaiable

Building the seed image needs about 4.5Gb of space. disk-image-create will use a
tempfs on those system with more than 4GB of RAM, with an free space by default up to 50%
of the RAM available so those system with 8GB or less will fail to build the image.

Test that there is more than 9GB RAM avaible or avoid the use of tempfs to create the seed image.
This can be override by using the env variable DIB_NO_TMPFS=[0|1].

Change-Id: Iede5bf9d50f548805a79e72b3f8cf074bc3e6b3e
'}]
commit_message:
Avoid using tempfs by default when not enough RAM avaiable

Building the seed image needs about 4.5Gb of space. disk-image-create will use a
tempfs on those system with more than 4GB of RAM, with an free space by default up to 50%
of the RAM available so those system with 8GB or less will fail to build the image.

Test that there is more than 9GB RAM avaible or avoid the use of tempfs to create the seed image.
This can be override by using the env variable DIB_NO_TMPFS=[0|1].

Change-Id: Iede5bf9d50f548805a79e72b3f8cf074bc3e6b3e

commit_message:
Removed the need for a domain in the 3PAR docs

The 3PAR drivers need to support CPGs that are not part of a
virtual domain on the 3PAR backend. This patch updates the Admin
Guide to remove the need for the CPG to be part of a domain.

Change-Id: I84639806c2d0be8a6622d44b615f366e4cf46881
Fixes: bug 1214076

commit_message:
Add how to update a default quota value for Compute.

Partial-Bug: #1195571

Also, Admin User and Compute Admin guides basically
need the same quota info. So split out Compute and
Block Storage-specific info from the
section_cli_set_quotas.xml file so that they can be
separately referenced. section_cli_set_quotas.xml
and section_compute-configure-quotas.xml file now
reference new xml files.

Change-Id: I56410fe308d05a3e8b7381423e2e6adc25cca9c9

commit_message:
Use system locale when Accept-Language header is not provided

Remove en_US as the default language when no header is provided, and use
None instead. Upon translation None will be defaulted to system as it
was before the translation changes.

Fixes bug 1214476

Change-Id: Ia18ae76f9dc3c93c7d14203af6f65b916500927e

commit_message:
Use swift_config to configure swift.conf

This change also adds an autorequire in the swift_config
type to ensure the /etc/swift/swift.conf exists.

Change-Id: Ic591a3ceb040c4599339ed7f750a5273d2052ac1
Implements: blueprint puppet-swift-ini-settings

I'll add this description with next patch.

Thank you."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-08-08 09:43:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

First I'd like to say that introducing rootwrap to a project that doesn't use it yet should really be seen as an extreme solution. It significantly weakens the security model by allowing limited privilege escalation from the glance user to root. So before accepting this you should ask yourself the question: is the added functionality worth the loss of security ?

This was raised in the past and the answer was that Glance should grow generic Cinder support rather than get into the business of handling specific backends and therefore abstain to grow rootwrap dependency.

On the patch itself, I find it weird that you'd introduce a new parameter and call it deprecated (root_helper). And introduce another parameter (rootwrap_config) but not use it at all.

processutils's method only uses root_helper, so it's a bit dated. If you want to use rootwrap_config instead, you should use something like https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/utils.py#L159 and not introduce root_helper at all."}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-08-09 07:27:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Do not merge

Hi,

As Thierry does, I think rootwrap shouldn't be pulled into Glance. 

I know there's a patch depending on this one, lets sort out all our doubts there before reconsidering this one.

commit_message:
Add rootwrap

Some of the glance's components require
root priveleges. This patch allows to use
rootwrap from the OpenStack common library.

Change-Id: I26081e1455c10714776160651e5adcfa6346a2b8

A few comments inline"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2013-08-01 14:39:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 8338, 'date': '2013-08-01 15:00:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Live snapshots of a domain, if you intend to roll back the state of that same domain, are okay.  But live snapshots of a domain, where you then use that snapshot as the basis of trying to create a new domain with different name, uuid, mac address, and such, can't POSSIBLY work.  Rewriting a "warn snapshot" in an attempt to clone a running domain to create other running domains without booting from scratch is doomed to fail, unless you can GUARANTEE that you have scrubbed every last address in guest RAM that refers to the old values.  And determining where in RAM the kernel and user space has referred to old values is not trivial - it depends on the software running in the guest.  You should NOT be trying to create a new domain by rewriting domain XML of a snapshot before restoring the snapshot.'}, {'account_id': 67, 'date': '2013-08-01 18:02:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: (4 inline comments)

Dan, Eric: I think this is a very limited view. This approach does work. Clearly there are caveats and you can't just take any arbitrary image, clone it and expect it to be functional.  The main purpose of something like this is simply to avoid boot time. Just because it requires a specially crafted image doesn't necessarily mean it isn't useful."}, {'account_id': 67, 'date': '2013-08-01 18:06:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-08-08 21:16:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

@Eric - seems to me that as long as the domains are defined with the same CPU/memory etc, the only in-Guest things that are being mutated is the MAC address of the nics: what about if we hot unplug them, snapshot, then hot plug (both in the original vm and hot plug in the new VM).

If there are concerns about breaking apps bound to the interface/ip address - they will break when the ip is rebound in the new VM anyway, so don't matter at this layer."}, {'account_id': 8338, 'date': '2013-08-08 21:41:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: No score

It's not just IP and MAC addresses that must be unique between guests.  For example, you MUST scrub ALL kernel random number state if you expect your clone to be secure against attacks where knowing the random stream in one side of the fork lets you predict the stream in the other side. I'm no crypto expert, but I _do_ know that failure to do this can lead to NASTY security problems. The 'virt-sysprep' tool (part of libguestfs) covers a large laundry list of things that must be scrubbed for an offline clone, and by introducing live cloning into the picture, you must scrub the same sort of content, no matter where it has been cached in guest memory - and knowing WHERE in guest memory something lives that must be scrubbed is dependent on the guest you are running.  You are falling foul of thinking that this is easier than it really is - to get a SECURE and reliable live clone, it is a LOT more work than just changing MAC addresses."}, {'account_id': 67, 'date': '2013-08-14 23:33:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-15 01:09:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
libvirt: Adds support for live-snapshot.

Also renames the existing methods called live_snapshot to
warm_snapshot. This better reflects what the methods are doing,
i.e. taking a snapshot of the disk without shutting the vm
down first.

Part of blueprint live-snapshot-vms

Change-Id: Iab6836a4307770a9b1391511ea7488c08a8f430e

commit_message:
Trove - Security Group Rule To/From Port options in the client

The CLI command to create a Security Group Rule makes the from/to port options required fields.
Since only instances listening on port 3306 are supported,
this fix removes the from/to port options from the troveclient

Change-Id: Ice1b776e82653e847776ee9e53ee54ef4cbdb450
Fixes: bug #1199623

commit_message:
Fix BaseException.message deprecation warnings

message attribute in Exception has been deprecated since python 2.6,add
a default value to support higher level Python Interpreter

Fixes: bug #1208666
Change-Id: I0688e09031b0b4674f5666e9fcd5cab69796563c

commit_message:
Use a global virtualenv

The distros hate it when we install over their stuff. I hate it too.
It's causing hives. It's also not proving anything to install via pip
globally.

Change-Id: Ibbd930ec8fc0900aeb6b85b4c5fa133d076b778d

[{'created': '2013-07-23 23:21:23.000000000', 'message': 'Add a random string to bm_poseur domain names

Running create-nodes multiple times failed unless bm_poseur
nodes were removed between calls. Using a random string instead
of a index allows create-nodes to be called multiple times. Effectively
allowing additional bm_poseurs to be added to an already running
undercloud.

Change-Id: I6a6091f1cba31036602473773de88a4fa261a889
'}]
commit_message:
Add a random string to bm_poseur domain names

Running create-nodes multiple times failed unless bm_poseur
nodes were removed between calls. Using a random string instead
of a index allows create-nodes to be called multiple times. Effectively
allowing additional bm_poseurs to be added to an already running
undercloud.

Change-Id: I6a6091f1cba31036602473773de88a4fa261a889

commit_message:
Include WWW-Authenticate header in 401 responses.

Include the WWW-Authenticate header when Keystone responds with 401 status code.
The format of the header is 'Keystone uri="%public_endpoint"' as indicated in http://docs.openstack.org/developer/keystone/middlewarearchitecture.html#exchanging-user-information .

Fixes: bug #1153719

Change-Id: I938ddceeaefd195e099dd922eccf91052cf9b2b6

commit_message:
Refactor OAuth consumer/token client instances

As per changes in keystoneclient, the manager referenced should
be prefixed with oauth_, as the terms consumers and tokens could
potentially be used in another context.

Change-Id: Ia70f709d9c57f58ff3dd5b84093647dbe7ba2f7b

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-14 20:01:32.000000000', 'message': "Refactor how we pick listings' content type.

There were a few different places where we had some repeated code to
figure out what format an account or container listing response should
be in (text, JSON, or XML). Now that's been pulled into a single
function.

As part of this, you can now raise HTTPException subclasses in proxy
controllers instead of laboriously plumbing error responses all the
way back up to swift.proxy.server.Application.handle_request(). This
lets us avoid certain ugly patterns, like the one where a method
returns a tuple of (x, y, z, error) and the caller has to see if it
got (value, value, value, None) or (None, None, None, errorvalue). Now
we can just raise the error.

Change-Id: I316873df289160d526487ad116f6fbb9a575e3de
"}, {'created': '2013-08-16 23:45:45.000000000', 'message': "Refactor how we pick listings' content type.

As part of this, you can now raise HTTPException subclasses in proxy
controllers instead of laboriously plumbing error responses all the
way back up to swift.proxy.server.Application.handle_request(). This
lets us avoid certain ugly patterns, like the one where a method
returns a tuple of (x, y, z, error) and the caller has to see if it
got (value, value, value, None) or (None, None, None, errorvalue). Now
we can just raise the error.

Change-Id: I316873df289160d526487ad116f6fbb9a575e3de
"}]
commit_message:
Refactor how we pick listings' content type.

There were a few different places where we had some repeated code to
figure out what format an account or container listing response should
be in (text, JSON, or XML). Now that's been pulled into a single
function.

As part of this, you can now raise HTTPException subclasses in proxy
controllers instead of laboriously plumbing error responses all the
way back up to swift.proxy.server.Application.handle_request(). This
lets us avoid certain ugly patterns, like the one where a method
returns a tuple of (x, y, z, error) and the caller has to see if it
got (value, value, value, None) or (None, None, None, errorvalue). Now
we can just raise the error.

Change-Id: I316873df289160d526487ad116f6fbb9a575e3de

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-06 04:02:45.000000000', 'message': 'Pass the destination file name to download modules

Currently an open file like object is passed into the image service
and thus into the download modules.  This is a limiting for certain
optimization (system calls to copy, hard links, external services,
out of order protocols like bittorrent, etc).  This patch passes the

commit_message:
Pass the destination file name to download modules

Currently an open file like object is passed into the image service
and thus into the download modules.  This is a limiting for certain
optimization (system calls to copy, hard links, external services,
out of order protocols like bittorrent, etc).  This patch passes the
file name into the image service when used by the nova.virt.images.
The previous means of passing in a data stream is still supported
but cannot be used with download modules.

Change-Id: Id17d426faab8d63dcffca22b300ebac3f15c104a
blueprint: image-multiple-location

'}, {'created': '2013-08-23 09:18:19.000000000', 'message': "Fix port creation issue appeared with postgresql backend

IPAllocation has relation to IPAvailabilityRange which is setup to
load eagerly. Eager loading is implemented with left outer join wich is
incompatible with with_lockmode('update') on postgresql.
The fix disables eager loading of particular query with enable_eagerloads(False)
and uses explicit join on the same model (IPAvailabilityRange).

fixes bug 1215350

Change-Id: I148d37f2a1c2a340327d36c240eb8173aee9219a
"}, {'created': '2013-08-23 10:28:55.000000000', 'message': "Fix port creation issue appeared with postgresql backend

IPAllocationPool has relation to IPAvailabilityRange which is setup to
load eagerly. Eager loading is implemented with left outer join which is
incompatible with with_lockmode('update') on postgresql.
The fix redefines eager loading with options(joinedload) making it use
inner join.

fixes bug 1215350

Change-Id: I148d37f2a1c2a340327d36c240eb8173aee9219a
"}]
commit_message:
Fix port creation issue appeared with postgresql backend

IPAllocationPool has relation to IPAvailabilityRange which is setup to
load eagerly. Eager loading is implemented with left outer join which is
incompatible with with_lockmode('update') on postgresql.
The fix redefines eager loading with options(joinedload) making it use
inner join.

fixes bug 1215350

Change-Id: I148d37f2a1c2a340327d36c240eb8173aee9219a

commit_message:
Sync up with global requirements

This is a pull from openstack/requirements.

Note that pep8, pyflakes and flake8 are now specified
as deps in hacking, so we can remove those here.  Also
if we don't remove them then we run into version conflicts
when hacking tries to set things up.

Quick!!!  Before it changes again!

Change-Id: Ib35b58c01f8d5d066d559e8afe4ea02adf55db5d

commit_message:
Autoload Nova extensions

This patch adds logic to autoload standard novaclient extensions
(e.g. baremetal) and any third-party extensions that might
be installed. Thus, resource plugins that make use of
installed extensions are able to use the standard OpenStackClients
rather than have to a) subclass and override OpenStackClients
or b) create a shadow nova client within the resource plugin
with the desired extension loaded.

Change-Id: Ifdcaa896babda0e1e7e10a55253a8baa37582264

commit_message:
Update requirements

This is the fabulous result of running the update.py script from
openstack/requirements with this repository as the target. It therefore
updates all dependencies, with nice version numbers that this repository
have to use to work. It also fixes case on some dependencies.
This update also brings a brand shiny new setup.py automatically handled
and generate by this same openstack/requirements repository.

Change-Id: I22ec396e5fa802c1617514aa6df3ed82f05271b0

commit_message:
Support for wildcard in pipeline

This patch will support for wildcard in pipeline.yaml so we
can exclude things like !storage.objects.*

This patch is dedicated to Fei Long Wang who triggered my thought on the
subject and proposed a first implementation.

docImpact
Fixes bug 1209128

Change-Id: I09a805ea7c9313b45152672a63981d5d4c263601

We can only consider restoring backup resources during a rollback
operation. If they are present during a standard update, there is no way of
testing whether or not they match the new template definition, so we need
to treat them differently in this case.

Change-Id: Ibd73ed047486c253a6c06b7340a3a591f0fee3db
'}]
commit_message:
Add a "rollback" parameter to StackUpdate

We can only consider restoring backup resources during a rollback
operation. If they are present during a standard update, there is no way of
testing whether or not they match the new template definition, so we need
to treat them differently in this case.

Change-Id: Ibd73ed047486c253a6c06b7340a3a591f0fee3db

commit_message:
Always resolve properties against the current stack

During an update, resources can get moved around between stacks. Ensure
that the properties are always resolved against whatever the current stack
is, without needing to replace self.properties.

Change-Id: I09f984cdf4478ca7dda2b0a0f1aa5a63dd2c19bc

commit_message:
Deal with 501 errors from NVP correctly

This is done by adding the error code to the exception
handlers dictionary as done for other error codes.

Fixes bug #1215583

Change-Id: Ic876c6bccaf94cae626dfc908c4a34dfbcead406

commit_message:
Adds support for Neutron Firewall

Introduces the following Neutron Firewall as a Service (FWaaS)
components to Heat resources:
* Firewall
* FirewallPolicy
* FirewallRule

Change-Id: I646a1402a336e7cc7c88d555cc836614bda9dca2
Implements: blueprint fwaas-heat

[{'created': '2013-08-20 19:16:43.000000000', 'message': 'Use system locale when Accept-Language header is not provided

Remove en_US as the default language when no header is provided, and use
None instead. Upon translation None will be defaulted to system as it
was before the translation changes.

Fixes bug: #1214476

Change-Id: I0fe22c526710e69ae0731e7d0b42170e6f3a8523
'}]
commit_message:
Use system locale when Accept-Language header is not provided

Remove en_US as the default language when no header is provided, and use
None instead. Upon translation None will be defaulted to system as it
was before the translation changes.

Fixes bug: #1214476

Change-Id: I0fe22c526710e69ae0731e7d0b42170e6f3a8523

commit_message:
Add automated check of conf sample

This adds check_uptodate to run_tests and
tox.ini checks.

This also requires that we add novaclient to the
test-requires, since we try and poke at cinder/compute/nova.

There is another implementation in use to do this that
pulls in openstack.common.config.generator,
(see ceilometer project for a pretty slick impl), however
adding that also pulls in a rather large list of
updates and dependencies that quite frankly Cinder
doesn't need and the ones that we do use break
a number of things in Cinder.

There's also a number of additional options added
to generate_sample that I don't think we need right now.

In the future we'll probably want to go this route
but for now I'd just like to get automated checking
in place.

Change-Id: I91aa4d98f472ad5a3ece7773c75ee76d66adafc0

commit_message:
Update requirements from global requirements

This commit just syncs the tempest requirement list with what's in
the global requirements repo. We are already using them for running
in the gate and with devstack so there isn't a reason to update the
lists in the tempest repo. This commit also adds jsonschema to the
list of requirements. It was removed at one point because it caused
an issue with grenade but since the global requirements fix ups this
is no longer an issue.

Fixes bug 1205980

Change-Id: I406eddc0b2363c98035edef6fc651228a2bdd04f

commit_message:
Use the same root test class.

Instead of being strongly tied to unittest2 make
it easier for taskflow to switch to another root
class (testr?) by abstracting out the unittest2
usage. This also enables some useful functionality
to exist in that root test class that other tasks
can take advantage of.

Change-Id: I381b6fb07e47f984b44cde439a17f39a1c1d32ac

commit_message:
Add common code for CLI tools

This code is shared between python-*client packages and is
used in CLI tools (nova, glance, etc.):
* decorators: arg and unauthenticated;
* print_list and print_dict;
* get_password.

This code comes from novaclient/utils.py.

Implements: blueprint common-cli-utils

Change-Id: Ic4fd6b0e3539032b5839eaa0ca23e5fa16ce47e2

commit_message:
LazyPluggable is no longer used.

After adjusting the persistence layer
the existing class is not needed since
we allow for more than one impl to be
active.

Change-Id: Ia59bc58902de8f63a08268dd639e10b7d246ecc7

commit_message:
LazyPluggable is no longer used.

After adjusting the persistence layer
the existing class is not needed since
we allow for more than one impl to be
active.

Change-Id: I54acbc845aefd8559872ef970459cf1bc520ccc5

commit_message:
Reformat help outputs

Reformatted the help outputs in the swift client to bring them more
in line with the rest of the openstack clients. Changes were added to
all of the st_command_help variables and a new variable
st_command_options was added to help with correct formatting of
help outputs.

Change-Id: I0c549cf96292384ddb36b43ecec41a883d8b2e13
Implements: changes to help outputs

'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-07-01 02:50:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

Hi Josh,

I am not convinced we really need green threads what we are really trying to improve is the following:
 Imagine 3 servers:

 (old way)
 for each server:
   nova.boot()
   while state != ACTIVE:
     sleep(X)

 (new'ish way)
 To me the main thing is that this is not done totally serially, but like this:

  task 1: actually call nova.boot(1)
  -> task 2: check status (status == BUILD)
  task 3: call nova.boot(2)
  -> task 4: check status (status == BUILD)
  task 5: call nova.boot(3)
  -> task 6: check status (status == BUILD)
  (do other stuff, while the servers are building...)
  -> task 2: check status (status == ACTIVE)
  -> task 4: check status (status == ACTIVE)
  -> task 6: check status (status == ACTIVE)
 (all done)

 So obviously greenthreads solves the problem, but makes taskflow quite complex.

 The Task could also return the task status (for the in-progress/pending) case and the you do other tasks and later when you run out of things to do go through the pending tasks and call check_state()."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-07-01 04:50:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

Interesting.

So your concept there could be just 2 greenthreads (?)

One u could call the 'run things' thread (that would do the nova boots) and the second u could call the 'idler thread' that would do things at a slower rate when the tasks the 'run things' thread has started are all in progress (check statuses).

This does seem possible if thats what u are thinking :-)

I wonder if there is value in having that either be a subclass of this pattern (or something new). Unsure."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-07-01 22:29:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 14.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-01 22:30:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: Doesn't seem to work

'}, {'created': '2013-06-26 06:40:25.000000000', 'message': 'Add a parallel flow using threads.

Propose a new graph flow that will run every task
in the graph at the same time but will use a count
down latch concept to ensure that a tasks dependents
are provided before the task itself can run. This
allows for tasks to run in parallel (if they have
no dependents or if seperate parts of the graph have
dependents meant at the same time).

commit_message:
Add a locally running threaded flow

Propose a new graph flow that will run every task
in the graph at the same time but will use a count
down latch concept to ensure that a tasks dependents
are provided before the task itself can run. This
allows for tasks to run in parallel (if they have
no dependents or are placed in disjoint parts of
graph).

Note: although this flow uses threads it is typically
expected that the underlying threads would be greenthreads
since python native threading is still suboptimal (for
various reasons).

Implements: blueprint locally-run-many-at-once

Change-Id: If434abd77758aa12fc99da395a2559995305a853

commit_message:
Sync execute() related exceptions with oslo

Cinder has its own ProcessExecutionError exception defined which
already exists in processutils.py. This was done to have minimal
editing when applying processutils.execute() to Cinder. As a result,
new instances are being created for each exception raised during
cli processing using execute()

As for the first step to remove the redundant excptions, this
patch syncs ProcessExecutionError and UnknownArgumentError
with that in processutils to ease the transition.

Change-Id: I88d9b86a0486f5d91fdcb664c99a9a2cd1392460

commit_message:
Switch gating tox jobs to testr parallel

This commit will migrate all gating tox jobs to use testr with the
--parallel flag. The smoke tox job is left serial because neutron
doesn't work with tempest in parallel.

Part of bp speed-up-tempest

Change-Id: I1e6eb9c7ce4d55010844ce3b6ca10dd20e7359b4

commit_message:
Merge with Oslo (master/ded9bd6)

Merges with current master of oslo-incubator, which brings
in several Python 3.x and other code fixes:

    ded9bd6  Make dependency on netaddr optional
    c331e74  Enable multiple translation domains for gettextutils
    17df920  Allow mapping _ to lazy gettext path
    ed653bf  Fix Message format-string parsing
    3198881  Add common methods required to allow translation of REST API responses
    df3f2ba  BaseException.message is deprecated since Python 2.6
    79ee367  Add more robust gettext interpolation handling
    45e0cbe  python3: Add basic python3 compatibility.
    1a2df89  Enable H302 hacking check
    d28fa69  python3: Add python3 compatibility.
    7b7566b  Add netaddr.IPAddress support to to_primitive()
    67bd769  python3: Fix traceback while running python3.
    b0c51ec  Refactors to_bytes
    472d8ed  Add slugify to strutils
    7119e29  Enable hacking H404 test.
    4246ce0  Added common code into fileutils and strutils.
    e3545f8  Enable hacking H402 test
    484a1df  Enable hacking H403 test
    50cae76  Add basic lazy gettext implementation
    536c39e  Add 't', 'y', and `strict` to `bool_from_string`
    d9b0719  Handle ints passed to `boolean_from_string`
    fde1e15  Convert unicode for python3 portability
    8c964a2  Do not import openstack.common.log in strutils
    9dcf688  Optimise to_primitive common cases
    e700d92  Replaces standard logging with common logging
    c8f676b  Support overriding oslo localedir too
    d8b66c7  Add a gettextutils.install() helper function
    f75126c  gettextutils: fix translation domain
    547ab34  Fix Copyright Headers - Rename LLC to Foundation
    2cb8e45  support ISO 8601 micro-second precision
    4eae556  Don't LOG.error on max_depth (by default).
    bd5dad9  Decode / Encode string utils for openstack
    a94b9b4  to_primitive imposes what seems to be an arbitary data structure
    a878193  Allow to_primitive to ignore datetimes
    1461135  timeutils: considers that now is soon
    a956f7a  Import timeutils.is_soon from keystoneclient
    d3a4c8e  UTC ISO8601 from timestamp
    33b12d3  Implement importutils.try_import.
    a08daf1  Use basestring instead of str for type check.

Change-Id: I7dc12e23ba89b74a3beeb49c24986110bd1682c6

commit_message:
Ensure that qpid connection is closed (from oslo)

This is commit a9bc62814d in oslo-incubator

Fixes bug 1172922

When reestablishing a session and a connection already exists the
existing connection will be closed prior to opening the new one.

Change-Id: I9a25800fe4b56eba89d550e3461ce095bf902f0a

commit_message:
Fix various cells issues due to object changes

1) Child cell scheduling fails.  The change to use Instance.create() in
child cells broke things.  The instance properties was being overwritten
due to a typo.  I also found a number of other things that need to be
popped out before passing to create_db_entry_for_new_instance().

2) Notification to the API cell was failing.  We cannot pass an object to
instance_update_at_top().

3) When cells is enabled, deleting an instance hits the '_local_delete'
part of code in the API because we don't see the compute node.  There's
a trap in cells_api.py to forward the delete on to child cells, but we
need to make sure not to try to deallocate network in the API cell.

Fixes bug 1216113

Change-Id: Ie989c22cb3b6a1359a0540e60e06fa4153e93476

commit_message:
Allow Cinder to specify file format for NFS/GlusterFS

These drivers now have the option of passing a QCOW2 file rather
than a raw file as the volume to attach to the VM.

Required by blueprint qemu-assisted-snapshots

Change-Id: I23929538c7dad65035db5c38ff6e52348925fa27

commit_message:
Support ipsec_site_connection status updating

In this commit, we implement status update for
ipsec_site_connection. The status field of ipsec_site_connection
will be updated automatically.

This commit also introduces helper function of which
check status is in pending status or not.

Implements blueprint ipsec-vpn-reference
Change-Id: Ief7e9cde480ac9d3901679f8cb2245108e626660

commit_message:
Support openswan device driver on VPN

This commit adds openswan support because RHEL
supports OpenSwan only.
Also, this commit makes OpenSwan driver as default
driver because it has wider OS support.

Implements blueprint ipsec-vpn-reference
Change-Id: I005bd15f666639f59a282eecbc6db07b3377fdaf

neutron vpn-ikepolicy-show displays "lifetime" as a field with default parameters. But there is no any help text about that field. 

(neutron) vpn-ikepolicy-create help lifetime
Invalid values_specs lifetime

If there is no such field why is it displayed, if there is how are we supposed to change it? Some description or refactoring is needed badly here'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-08-01 11:53:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 34:

I agree with Tatiana that it is better lifetime and dpd are displayed
in the help message. (Of course it applies to sesession_persistence in lbaas.)

There are several possible solutions:
(1) Add --lifetime option: "--lifetime units=seconds,value=3600"
(2) Add --lifetime-units and --lifetime-value opiotns: "--lifetime-units seconds --lifetime-value 3600"
(3) Don't add options

In case of (1) or (2), "--lifetime type=dict units=seconds,value=3600" cannot be used at now.
This comes from two reasons: argparse behavior and unknown option handling in neutronclient.

I prefer to option (1).'}, {'account_id': 7016, 'date': '2013-08-02 03:51:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 35.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-02 04:37:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 35: Works for me

commit_message:
VPN as a Service (VPNaaS) Client API

Implements:blueprint VPNaaS-Python-API

This provides the basic Neutron Client
CLI for configuring:
* VPNService
* IKEPolicy
* IPsecPolicy
* IPsecSiteConnection

Change-Id: I72ab670d23109a4bb1174acf48e4b77958e855e1

commit_message:
Add the error reason to the Order entity if async processing fails.

When an Order is used to perform asynchronous actions such as creating secrets,
the client doesn't know what problem occurred unless they retrieve the metadata
for the given order later. This metadata should both indicate that the order
status is ERROR, and provide an error reason for the failure.

Change-Id: Ib10e831cc98c20a77ed502e885687447e874e05c
Implements: blueprint api-orders-add-error-reason

commit_message:
Improve the error msg of v2 image_data.py

Based on current implement, the error message of some upload
failures is missing the image id. It looks like: 'Unable to
upload duplicate image data for image: %s'.

Fixes bug 1207616

Change-Id: I608fb1ba84dde0e44a73e5e1bd3e850db49d84c4

commit_message:
Remove the rest references to exception.py

Remove the rest references to Oslo exception.py in Heat code base, so that Oslo
maintainer can go ahead and remove the openstack/common/exception.py file.

Change-Id: I19d325e2117f31a887c593e31b61e25729f7a053

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-12 11:18:00.000000000', 'message': "Set bootable flag for volume cloned from image

In previous code we don't set the bootable flag for volume
cloned from image,This does not appear to break booting

commit_message:
Set bootable flag for volume cloned from image

In previous code we don't set the bootable flag for volume
cloned from image. This does not appear to break booting
from volume at present but the status displayed by the cinder
client is broken.

The bug is reported and fixed several months ago(bug #1185533)
but the author doesn't provide unit test with the patch. Now it
has been broken again by somebody else.The patch re-fixed this
bug together with unit tests.

Also add a function named _handle_bootable_volume_glance_meta,
it is a combination of enable_bootable_flag and glance_metadata
handling. There are 3 kinds of volume creation tasks may required
to copy/fetch the glance metadata. In previous code every kind of
task have its own handling code, this patch consolidate them together
to share some common code.

fixed bug #1211272
fixed bug #1185533

Change-Id: I86007e26efbebe58dc0c5995b6f14f68258144b5

commit_message:
Configure bash completion

Add bash completion rules to the /etc/bash_completion.d from the
 cinder, neutron, keystone, nova and nova-manage.

This is very fast operation and makes the cli usage easier.

Change-Id: Icdcdaf55d58efaaa1afe25fd55f088bf7dc8b3f1

commit_message:
Add ComputeNode object implementation

This adds a ComputeNode object with proper linkage to the Service
object.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I83412a0b07d3a5a0cef1117641e56d02dc41ba6a

commit_message:
[v3] Show detail of an quota in API os-quota-sets

nova-manage shows `in_use`, `reserved` including `limit` of a quota.
So create a new API named `detail` to do the same with nova-manage.

The new URL is like :/v3/os-quota-sets/1234/detail.

Fix bug: #1183870

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ic53a68acf0f3f3184c7a900360343bb576560f46

commit_message:
Inherit base image properties on instance creation

When starting an instance, a few properties from the image will be saved
in the instance's system_metadata under the prefix 'image_'. This way,
when creating an snapshot, resizing, migrating or rescuing an instance
we can preserve the original properties even if the source image has
been deleted or made private.

This is done by adding two utility functions that translate the image
metadata into system metadata and vice versa. These are  used from the
operations specified before to complement the image metadata and
preventing them to fail if the image doesn't exist.

The keys that the instance will inherit from the image are: 'min_ram',
'min_disk', 'disk_format' and 'container_format' together with the
inheritable image properties.

Fixes bug #1039662

Change-Id: If6a7b182a2fb46cdd05bd19760fcd246442b7f4b

Other projects, including nova and oslo.db, use _pre_upgrade_### as the
function to run before a DB migration test. This is to differentiate it

Change-Id: I0da30f7c5a1c76a7ff0e735c36b753ef7a624db9

commit_message:
Use _pre_upgrade_### instead of _prerun_###

Other projects, including nova and oslo.db, use _pre_upgrade_### as the
function to run before a DB migration test. This is to differentiate it
from the downgrade tests.

Change-Id: I0da30f7c5a1c76a7ff0e735c36b753ef7a624db9

commit_message:
Add domain attributes to accessinfo

user_domain_id and project_domain_id are already available, so simply
add an equivalent user_domain_name and project_domain_name if available.

The use of 'default' for v2 tokens is inspired from the default behaviour of
similar functions and what is used in auth_token middleware.

Change-Id: Ia9b345529072ab893d04c7a38fb7ba3acdc28227

commit_message:
Make compute_api use KeyPair objects

This makes compute_api's KeypairAPI use KeyPair objects to do
its work. Most of the change here is to tests to account for the
change.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: If516a88eac107670d9ae37fcfaf56f2add9dd0c5

commit_message:
Allow tests to run without installation

This patch makes modifications to the way that programs which the various
tests depend on are forked and executed.  This will allow the tests to be
run without installing glance to a python installation (ie: python setup.py
{develop/install} will not be needed).

fixes bug: 1197800

Change-Id: I9687cb7a5b22747d9cea0a1c24057383a8901476

commit_message:
Offline snapshots for GlusterFS volumes

Offline snapshots for the GlusterFS driver, based
on QCOW2 snapshotting.

This introduces the option to have volumes stored as
qcow2 files rather than raw files. (glusterfs_qcow2_volumes)

Bump driver version to 1.1.0.

This patch requires Nova to support loading qcow2 disks:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38321/

Online snapshot support (via Nova) is added in a
subsequent patch submitted in this series.

This patch also enables volume cloning for GlusterFS volumes.

Implements blueprint qemu-assisted-snapshots

Change-Id: I783a802574b835b495e343f555f7ecf9b46981dd

commit_message:
Use hashed token for invalid PKI token cache key

Invalid PKI tokens are cached in memcache using the entire token as
key. This triggers the familiar memcache key length error since a
PKI token is much longer than 250 characters.

This change hashes the token before using it as a key, and also changes
instances of "token" to "token_id" where appropriate so it's clear
that we're passing around a hashed token rather than the token data
itself.

Change-Id: I765b209578d60266da706094f61d8d9b15cfb6de
Closes-bug: 1206347

commit_message:
Support older token formats for projects in accessinfo

Older token formats get decoded as a v2 token so we should support
reading project information from these tokens.

Change-Id: I31473a00b294bd0d7b535cfab8d2eaf09db97ff5

Add KeyPair object

This adds a KeyPair object implementation for use by compute_api.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

commit_message:
Make size/checksum immutable for active images

Once an image becomes 'active' it should only be possible for an
administrator (and not a regular user) to change the size and checksum
values.

Addresses bug 1209148.

Change-Id: Ic65afbca4a4161dfa77ce0a296a1bd72d96902ca

[{'created': '2013-08-20 09:59:19.000000000', 'message': "Upgrade setuptools to 1.10 or more in a newly created virtualenv

By default, virtualenv embeds setuptools, and doesn't download its latest version.
At the moment, latest virtualenv is 1.10.1, which does install setuptools-0.9.8

Unfortunately, setuptools-0.9.8 doesn't manage correctly HTTPS certificates if the user is specifying a proxy with https_proxy and http_proxy environments variables.
This can raise an error if the server to download is having TLS2_3 HTTPS certificate, by example when pip installing python-novaclient, whick asks for https://pypi.python.org/simple/pbr

Change-Id: I7cca000857f7691d4cb723d0a0c22a202da703f8
"}, {'created': '2013-08-26 09:27:57.000000000', 'message': "Upgrade setuptools to 1.10 or more in a newly created virtualenv

http_proxy environments variables. This can raise an error if the

pip installing python-novaclient, whick asks for
https://pypi.python.org/simple/pbr

Fixes: bug #1201253
Change-Id: I7cca000857f7691d4cb723d0a0c22a202da703f8

commit_message:
Upgrade setuptools to 1.10 or more in a newly created virtualenv

By default, virtualenv embeds setuptools, and doesn't download its
latest version. At the moment, latest virtualenv is 1.10.1, which does
install setuptools-0.9.8

Unfortunately, setuptools-0.9.8 doesn't manage correctly HTTPS
certificates if the user is specifying a proxy with https_proxy and
http_proxy environments variables. This can raise an error if the
server to download is having TLS2_3 HTTPS certificate, by example when
pip installing python-novaclient, whick asks for
https://pypi.python.org/simple/pbr

Fixes: bug #1201253
Change-Id: I7cca000857f7691d4cb723d0a0c22a202da703f8

commit_message:
Add a pip-cache element.

The element bind mounts a pip cache inside the image build chroot so
that pip downloads can be reused across image builds.  While similar
in purpose to the PyPi element that sets up a mirror, this element
just allows for a reusable download cache and doesn't require anything
to be setup beforehand.

The pip-cache element is not concurrency safe, and that is indicated
in the README for the element.  An upstream bug was file as well:
https://github.com/pypa/pip/issues/1141

Change-Id: Ibd1d4ea17c24923ed939357ada95b781e3179cfd

commit_message:
Stop validating individiual xml files

This patch stops the tools/validate.py script from checking individual
XML files against the DocBook schema.

Since this script now attempts to build all books, there's no need
for individual file checks like this. In addition, I think the schema
that this script is checking against is slightly different than the
one that we are using to generate the docs, leading to false
positivies.

Change-Id: I1ac5ff83245823f98aa82cd87f09f680d52b3df2

commit_message:
Improve EC2 API error responses

Proper EC2 error codes are returned where possible.

EC2APIError was removed and replaced by new specific exceptions with
ec2_code attribute.

Fault wrapper now returns actual EC2 error code instead of HTTP
status code which was ridiculously incorrect behavior. Fault:__call__
wasn't covered by any unit tests, so I added one.

Implements: blueprint ec2-error-codes
Change-Id: Ib6580d12e88a94396c350eae6ca2697bee8d5580

commit_message:
Use system locale when Accept-Language header is not provided

Remove en_US as the default language when no header is provided, and use
None instead. Upon translation None will be defaulted to system as it
was before the translation changes.

Fixes bug: #1214476

Change-Id: Ice7f55912a7bd6c727a7f8a2a1172871fe27a3dc

Upgrading 'stevedore' module for bug 1169730

https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/cinder/+bug/1169730
Running into this on Ubuntu 12.04

Simply upgrading to a newer 'stevedore' resolved the issues with
the cinder scheduler.

commit_message:
Do not have the runner modify the uuid

The uuid is used for result tracking and
prefixing it with 'r-' makes it hard to
find that uuid later so leave the uuid
that is selected as is.

Change-Id: I05fed5c197a8d9dc41daedc630ecfa22145bd46c

[{'created': '2013-08-23 10:49:12.000000000', 'message': 'Separate l3 db tests for l3 agent into their own test case

Bug 1215871

This patch does a simple refactoring of test_l3_plugin, pushing out tests
aimed at validating the interactions of the l3 agent with the server.

These tests explicitly use TestL3NatPlugin, whereas all the
other tests use a configurable plugin, which might be specificed by a child
class. This might lead to confusion and possibly errors in unit tests for
child classes, especially those not using the l3 agent - for which running
these test is also superfluous.

Change-Id: Ia9ed320ea775fc548e6a5b711c67c9f3b0ae2f6d
'}]
commit_message:
Separate l3 db tests for l3 agent into their own test case

Bug 1215871

This patch does a simple refactoring of test_l3_plugin, pushing out tests
aimed at validating the interactions of the l3 agent with the server.

These tests explicitly use TestL3NatPlugin, whereas all the
other tests use a configurable plugin, which might be specificed by a child
class. This might lead to confusion and possibly errors in unit tests for
child classes, especially those not using the l3 agent - for which running
these test is also superfluous.

Change-Id: Ia9ed320ea775fc548e6a5b711c67c9f3b0ae2f6d

Hi Eirc,

I agree with you that it isn't reasonable for the unit tests to require cinder to be installed, but skipping a test because of this is worse in my book as it hides this fact and we continue blissfully unaware that something is wrong.

The real problem is that the scheduler itself requires too much infrastructure to run at all. It loads all the dependencies of cinder requiring that they be installed and new enough according to requirements.txt If this was fixed then we could just specify the filters from cinder that we want to test. The tests won't require all of cinder to be installed then.

commit_message:
Re-enable a lot of cinder scheduler tests

This highlight and fixes a NoneType exception in the schedulers
_get_weighted_candidates method

This was originally added to get around the fact that the filter tests
required that cinder was correctly installed on the system. But the
is_cinder_installed condition always returning False and this hid
problems of old packages been installed in our system. Also
930f5891b0815e1b49b9b2cc840e0c24b2796e84 added the setup.py automatically
to run_tests.sh so we can remove this.

See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/20213/ for history.

Fixes bug: 1213226

Change-Id: I86fee802c0543355471ddbd712e52ccec750cea0

commit_message:
Rework the persistence layer

1. Simplify the exposed api to reduce race conditions
   which could occur if we allowed flow details, task
   details and log books to be deleted at different
   times; reduce this down to just being able to save and
   delete from logbooks (and only save/update for flow
   and task details to) to reduce the problem cases.
2. Introduce a alembic migration with a proper schema so that
   the initial database can be created in the first place,
   adjust its exposed fields and relations to be defined
   by said schema.
3. Use oslo db models instead of our own.

Change-Id: I78bbedf87d506d3f39157198638937c933235b7b

commit_message:
Fix for openrc download on Firefox if the project contains blanks

When downloading the openrc file or the ec2 credentials file on
horizon of a tenant that contains blanks, on firefox the filename
gets truncated up to the first space.

Change-Id: I08bc5f2f8d28584423e3f6eb6a781ab0384aa4d5
Fixes: bug 1215923

commit_message:
Use latest Oslo's version

The patch replaces current Oslo version with 1.2. The change is needed
to pull in a fix released in that specific version, which fixes the
issue #1175570. The fix we're interested in is giving priority to CLI
arguments instead of config files. Without this, commands like the one
below won't work.

    $ glance-manage --sql_connection=.... db_sync

Oslo's release notes:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.config/#a3

Closes-Bug: #1175570
Change-Id: I4ea749cfaae0e18e035abe7b5d7e345dda7d476d

commit_message:
Testing how .html files are rendered by cgit

This patch is a hand generated .html file from README.rst.
I would like to see how it appears in cgit, in order to evaluate if it is
worthwhile to pursue my current path to render .rst files as .html files in
cgit.

Change-Id: Ic78729632a95c2c44ad32cdf5732dd6d82f6a1b0

commit_message:
Fix translate static messages in response

Messages created statically (during import) were not being
translated in responses when the Accept-Language header was
used to set the expected language in the response. The static
messages were being created before the _ built-in had been
installed by gettextutils.install().

Change-Id: Ie56b1d3a836bc5f2262d7af68f803a08ebdf016f
Resolves-Bug: #1215192

[{'created': '2013-07-25 15:33:57.000000000', 'message': 'Added iPXE boot support.

Change-Id: I33acf9dfdff0a5ed9797723a142bc451348e8549
'}, {'created': '2013-07-25 16:10:09.000000000', 'message': 'xenapi: Added iPXE ISO boot support

This gives customers (of service-providers running XenAPI) a means to roll
their own image.

The service-provider supplies an ISO with iPXE support rolled into it and then
the customer can choose that image, boot to an OS of their choosing, then the
customize the image in anyway they want.

Two virt-layer modifications were needed. The first was adding configurations
for the iPXE ISO feature (network to use, boot menu, mkisofs_cmd). The second
was the ability to inject networking info into the ISO after it was
downloaded.

This was accomplished via a new post-image-download hook (fixup_disks) and a
new dom0 plugin that knows how to mount an ISO, copy it, inject networking,
rebundle it, and place the modified version back into the SR.

Change-Id: I33acf9dfdff0a5ed9797723a142bc451348e8549

The service-provider supplies an ISO with iPXE support rolled into it and then
the customer can choose that image, boot to an OS of their choosing, then the
customize the image in anyway they want.

Two virt-layer modifications were needed. The first was adding configurations
for the iPXE ISO feature (network to use, boot menu, mkisofs_cmd). The second
was the ability to inject networking info into the ISO after it was
downloaded.

This was accomplished via a new post-image-download hook (fixup_disks) and a
new dom0 plugin that knows how to mount an ISO, copy it, inject networking,
rebundle it, and place the modified version back into the SR.

This patch adds support for a new kind of Glance image, a specially crafted ISO
which supports iPXE booting, giving customers a means to roll their own image.

Two virt-layer modifications were needed. The first was adding configurations

commit_message:
xenapi: Added iPXE ISO boot support

This patch adds support for a new kind of Glance image, a specially crafted ISO
which supports iPXE booting, giving customers a means to roll their own image.

Two virt-layer modifications were needed. The first was adding configurations
for the iPXE ISO feature (network to use, boot menu, mkisofs_cmd). The second
was the ability to inject networking info into the ISO after it was
downloaded.

To use this feature, operators should enable the `ipxe_boot` image-property.

DocImpact

Implements blueprint xenapi-ipxe-iso-boot-support

Change-Id: I33acf9dfdff0a5ed9797723a142bc451348e8549

commit_message:
Add resource tracking to build_and_run_instance

Resource tracker checking is added so that we have reasonable assurance
of being able to build the instance before it starts.  This allows for a
quick reschedule if the compute node does not have available resources.

This is one part of a series of patches to build up the
build_and_run_instance method.

Part of bp query-scheduler

Change-Id: Ife6e5aef4fda46f74e2db7be1a09b210be397152

commit_message:
close http connections

Running full tempest one might run out of file descriptors. httplib2
does not close the connection by default. This patch adds
connection:close header to every request, so that sockets won't be
hanging around.

fixes bug 1215804

Change-Id: Iea19936c45add98fc66588f623854e629cf448fb

commit_message:
The DB migration shouldn't populate types table

It is up to the system adminisator to do this via an API call.

Also fixes up a few cases of dict() being used rather than the prefered {}
(https://github.com/openstack-dev/hacking/blob/master/HACKING.rst#dictionarieslists)

Fixes bug: 1215962

Change-Id: I6b2eea0c03467b157ec147292dbea54e7f99006c

commit_message:
Skip orchestration scenario tests if heat service not available

The orchestration scenario tests were not previously checking if the
heat service is available as configured in tempest.conf like the other
service-specific tests. This patch adds that check.

Closes-Bug: #1216335

Change-Id: I10c66adc1bab103b45e2d49d4f005618f2031052

commit_message:
api: allow usage of resource_metadata in query

When returning samples, they have a field called resource_metadata, and
therefore it may seem nature to filter on it using this as a prefix in
queries. Let's allow use of it.

Fixes-Bug: #1195765

Change-Id: I82f591e0d38a3063a9762de1ac64dc3ef9d29ee7

commit_message:
jsonutils: make types py3 compatible

In Python 3, there's no long nor NoneType. Let's replace by equivalent
values.

Change-Id: Id1aa7af26b0f5d929337cc373c6a4f802bba2cec

jsonutils: do not require xmlrpclib

xmlrpclib isn't shipped anymore in Python 3, so let's support it
optionally.

commit_message:
Sources for hadoop-patch

Sources were obtained from https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/attachment/12583703/HADOOP-8545-033.patch
by running "patch" command. All the files related to Hadoop-common were skiped during patching.

Changes were made after patching:
* pom.xml was updated to use hadoop-core 1.1.2 dependency
* removed dependency on 2.x hadoop in code (@Override and isDirectory() -> isDir())
* removed Hadoop 2.X tests

There are no unit-tests, only integration.

Change-Id: I8d7c2f544d14f79597fcdefe27ecae0d43b6df9e

commit_message:
Fix figure filenames for customzing dashboard

FTP was unable to maintain emdash in file name,
removes emdash from file name and changes xml
source reference. Should be backported to
stable/grizzly also.

Fix bug 1210371

Change-Id: I2e66c55282cdd4f3459e7475863d7b4385a9016d

commit_message:
Bump hacking to 0.7

Disable H102, Apache 2.0 license header not found, until all 23 cases
are fixed.

Hacking 0.6 already pins down pep8, pyflakes and flake8 so they can be
removed from test-requirements as they are indirect dependencies.

Change-Id: Ica90ae153388e72fb234b6a5e7802d9e04ab681c

commit_message:
Support for wildcard in pipeline

This patch will support for wildcard in pipeline.yaml so we
can exclude things like !storage.objects.*

docImpact
Fixes bug 1209128

Change-Id: Ia496efa73fb012cfbb694b402ec6e949b89b75b5

commit_message:
Bump hacking to 0.7

hacking 0.6 already pins down pep8, pyflakes and flake8 so they can be
removed from test-requirements as they are indirect dependencies.

Fix python 3.x compatibility for print statements in tests (hacking 0.7
check), by switching over to logging instead.

Change-Id: I2fcf15fdf04b8897a0c95d5d9f757b96ce2adca7

commit_message:
Remove a useless arg in range()

Modify tests/test_v3_auth.py, remove the useless arg ("start index" = 0)
since its default value is 0. There was no range(0, N) being called in
any other place except here in keystone sources.

Change-Id: Ifce3384982476a7b9884a51aa73fdb45798e3051

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-26 08:24:12.000000000', 'message': "Remove check_for_lock support in RPCClient

I added check_for_lock because I assumed it was enabled by default and
actively in use by Nova. However, it actually isn't used by Nova yet and
enabling spews a tonne of warnings.

It's a rather clunky API and there's a good chance we can design a
better API for it, so let's leave it out until we're ready to actually
start using it in Nova.

Related-Bug: #1063222
Change-Id: Ib890978398059f360cd0f3352f4755262b8111c6
"}, {'created': '2013-08-26 08:31:27.000000000', 'message': "Remove check_for_lock support in RPCClient

commit_message:
Remove check_for_lock support in RPCClient

I added check_for_lock because I assumed it was enabled by default and
actively in use by Nova. However, it actually isn't used by Nova yet and
enabling spews a tonne of warnings.

It's a rather clunky API and there's a good chance we can design a
better API for it, so let's leave it out until we're ready to actually
start using it in Nova.

Related-Bug: #1063222
Change-Id: Ib890978398059f360cd0f3352f4755262b8111c6

commit_message:
Don't include msg_id or reply_q in casts

On the server side, we only send replies if the request included a
_msg_id key. Also, the _reply_q key is only used when we wish to send a
reply.

So, in order to retain the exact same on-the-wire behaviour and ensure
servers aren't sending replies where none is needed, only include these
keys if we're doing a call (i.e. wait_for_reply=True).

Change-Id: Iac329493252be7d94b1ebe24f00e4d3f5c61d269

[{'created': '2013-08-26 11:45:31.000000000', 'message': 'Fix race-condition in rabbit reply processing

Concurrency. Sigh.

A sequence of events like this is possible:

  - We send a request from thread A
  - Thread B, who is waiting for a response gets, scheduled
  - Thread B receives our response and queues it up
  - Thread B receives its own response and drops the connection lock
  - We grab the connection lock and wait for our response to arrive

The obvious solution is that when we grab the connection lock, we should

commit_message:
Fix race-condition in rabbit reply processing

Concurrency. Sigh.

A sequence of events like this is possible:

  - We send a request from thread A
  - Thread B, who is waiting for a response gets scheduled
  - Thread B receives our response and queues it up
  - Thread B receives its own response and drops the connection lock
  - Thread A grabs the connection lock and wait for a response to arrive

The obvious solution is that when we grab the connection lock, we should
check whether a previous lock-holding thread had already received our
response and queued it up.

Change-Id: I88b0d55d5a40814a84d82ed4f42d5ba85d2ef7e0

commit_message:
Refactored storage tests to use testscenarios

This refactore storage tests to use testscenarios

The test_impl_* files now have only test related the a particular
backend.

All common tests are in test_impl_scenarios.py (previously named
base.py)

The maxconns of Mongod have been increase to allow db2 to run

Parts of blueprint db-tests-with-scenarios

Change-Id: I94955ca1cead3f7c7e04b57b9ce1313324e4a349

commit_message:
Enable gre and vxlan with the same ID

Traffic is now sended in gre tunnels, or in vxlan tunnels,
depending on the network that it comes from.

Fixes bug #1196963

commit_message:
Clean up db.sqla.Models.extra_keys interface

Previously we were checking that Class has
_extra_keys() method and if it has then extend columns with this list.

It will be much cleaner to have in ModelBase this method so we will be able
to avoid this check,  and as method should contains verb we change the name
also to _get_extra_keys().

It changes API so we should also make related in other projects.
But there is not so much work (e.g. in Nova there are only 2 occurences)

Change-Id: Ib9f3a165fae340a1c887769ce8f21a70c28458d0
Closes-Bug: #1119717

commit_message:
Provide useful defaults for config generator

Right now if you run generate_sample.sh in (for example) Nova,
you have to provide all three parameters for it to work right.
This change tweaks the defaults so that the script can be run
from the root of the project directory with no parameters.
This should apply to all of the projects, not just Nova.

Closes-Bug: 1204204

Change-Id: Iaa0a899dd4f34f44317f9574688e305365a604bf

[{'created': '2013-08-26 09:38:40.000000000', 'message': 'Fix error message if message handler fails

There are a number of situations in which we log a message if an
exception occurs during the handling of a message:

  1) Something goes wrong pulling the message from the queue and
     de-serializing it - here we print "Failed to process message"

  2) An RPC endpoint method raises an expected exception - here we
     print an 'Expected exception during message handling' debug
     message

  3) An RPC endpoint method raises any other exception - here we
     should print an 'Exception during message handling' error message

However, in the latter case, we are currently printing out the 'Failed
to process' error message.

Change-Id: I4f7042b8ec978aaff8f4e20e62ba1ac765fe6ba5
'}]
commit_message:
Fix error message if message handler fails

There are a number of situations in which we log a message if an
exception occurs during the handling of a message:

  1) Something goes wrong pulling the message from the queue and
     de-serializing it - here we print "Failed to process message"

  2) An RPC endpoint method raises an expected exception - here we
     print an 'Expected exception during message handling' debug
     message

  3) An RPC endpoint method raises any other exception - here we
     should print an 'Exception during message handling' error message

However, in the latter case, we are currently printing out the 'Failed
to process' error message.

Change-Id: I4f7042b8ec978aaff8f4e20e62ba1ac765fe6ba5

Otherwise, if the goal is to use neutron to do load balancer things in the CFN namespace, wouldn't it be prudent to change the existing implementation of AWS::ElasticLoadBalancing::LoadBalancer to use Neutron LBaaS rather than an instance with ha_proxy?

I guess this boils down to my preference that we have native Openstack resources that reflect the underlying Openstack semantics and workflows over having resources that don't look or feel like either OS or CFN.'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2013-08-13 09:31:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I'm not sure what "native" means. The resource here is as close to neutron lbaas as it could be. The only concession I'm making is calling the attribute Instances for compatibility reasons (not only with CFN, but also our own OS::Heat::InstanceGroup resource). I could be closer to the underlying semantic and calling it members, but it wouldn't give us much benefit apart from being incompatible.

Changing AWS::ElasticLoadBalancing::LoadBalancer to use neutron lbaas is certainly interesting, but it's also a hard work, in particular because you need to keep the schema compatible.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-08-13 10:26:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

So, still thinking about this, but here's my thoughts so far..

- refactoring should be in a separate patch to the feature

- I don't think we should start reworking the AWS::ElasticLoadBalancing::LoadBalancer (internally defined) resource to use neutron, as therve says it will be a lot of work, and atm not everyone wants to use neutron so a non-neutron LB is useful.  However, it may make sense to see if we can reimplement it on top of this native resource via a provider template?

- The properties do look awkward.  I'm wondering if there's some other way to do it, as we don't want to start polluting the native interfaces with AWSisms IMO, even if it causes us some transitional pain aligning with all-native resources.  

The real problem here is we depend on the AWS properties inside the supposed-to-be native OS::Heat::InstanceGroup, which is unfortunate and historical, I'm not sure how we fix that without breaking InstanceGroup for existing users."}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2013-08-13 11:50:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Agreed with those points. One possible solution would be to give those resources an attribute (a python attribute or a template attribute), that InstanceGroup could inspect, which would told it where to look for instances. EG:

class LoadBalancer...

   instances_attribute = 'Instances'

class NeutronLoadBalancer...:

   instances_attribute = 'members'

The rackspace load balancer could also provide a compatibility properties taking nova server ids instead of 'nodes', but that's a different topic. I'm actually surprised to see that it doesn't work with InstanceGroup considering a refactoring has been done in that direction.

What I really want long term is to invert the relationship, and have a simple resource which create the link between a loadbalancer and a server. We need ResourceGroup like feature for that, though."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-08-13 15:53:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

+1 for ResourceGroup. Had some talks with radix around this allowing for arbitrary resources to be grouped so that may be a place to start there (at some point).

Another +1 for *eventually* inverting the relationship (at least for new/"native" resources) and allow the lb resources to derive their list of balanced resources via a relationship to a (Resource/Instance/Scaling)Group. In the meantime, an inspect-able property sounds reasonable in the interim.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-21 06:03:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-21 06:03:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2013-08-22 08:12:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Restored'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2013-08-22 08:12:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6800, 'date': '2013-08-22 16:35:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

Looks good to me, just some minor points."}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2013-08-23 08:40:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (3 inline comments)

commit_message:
Implement a load balancer resource using new neutron pool

It creates a new resource linking to a neutron pool, and taking a list
of servers to be linked to it.

Implements: blueprint lbaas-resource
Change-Id: Ie1590e12449a8e086eee7e7960a45103cbf20860

commit_message:
Allow in-place update of nested stack

Not raising UpdateReplace exception anymore for nested stack update.
Instead, propagating the update request to the nested stack, so that
the nested stack itself will decide the best way to handle the update
request for every of its resources.

blueprint nested-stack-updates

Change-Id: Ibfe7bee71fe57a601b93fa05a4a0c1cda972290e
